# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cryptocurrency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin works through the collaboration of computers, each of which acts as a node in the peer-to-peer bitcoin network.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Each node maintains an independent copy of a public distributed ledger of transactions, called a blockchain, without central oversight.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Transactions are validated through the use of cryptography, preventing one person from spending another person's bitcoin, as long as the owner of the bitcoin keeps certain sensitive data secret.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Consensus between nodes about the content of the blockchain is achieved using a computationally intensive process based on proof of work, called mining, which is performed by purpose-built computers.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Mining consumes large quantities of electricity, with surveyed miners reporting that 52% of their electricity use came from sustainable energy sources, and has been criticized for its environmental impact.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Before bitcoin, several digital cash technologies were released, starting with David Chaum's ecash in the 1980s.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The idea that solutions to computational puzzles could have some value was first proposed by cryptographers Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor in 1992.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The concept was independently rediscovered by Adam Back who developed Hashcash, a proof-of-work scheme for spam control in 1997.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The first proposals for distributed digital scarcity-based cryptocurrencies came from cypherpunks Wei Dai (b-money) and Nick Szabo (bit gold) in 1998.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2004, Hal Finney developed the first currency based on reusable proof of work.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] These various attempts were not successful: Chaum's concept required centralized control and no banks wanted to sign on, Hashcash had no protection against double-spending, while b-money and bit gold were not resistant to Sybil attacks.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The domain name *bitcoin.org* was registered on 18 August 2008.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] On 31 October 2008, a link to a white paper authored by Satoshi Nakamoto titled *Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System* was posted to a cryptography mailing list.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to computer scientist Arvind Narayanan, all individual components of bitcoin originated in earlier academic literature.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nakamoto's innovation was their complex interplay which resulted in the first decentralized, Sybil resistant, Byzantine fault tolerant digital cash system, that would eventually be referred to as the first blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nakamoto's paper was not peer-reviewed and was initially ignored by academics, who argued that it could not work.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nakamoto released bitcoin as open-source software.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] On 3 January 2009, the bitcoin network was created when Nakamoto mined the starting block of the chain, known as the *genesis block*.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Embedded in this block was the text "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks", which is the date and headline of an issue of *The Times* newspaper.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nine days later, Hal Finney received the first bitcoin transaction: ten bitcoins from Nakamoto.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Wei Dai and Nick Szabo were also early supporters.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] On May 22, 2010, the first known commercial transaction using bitcoin occurred when programmer Laszlo Hanyecz bought two Papa John's pizzas for ₿10,000, in what would later be celebrated as "Bitcoin Pizza Day".
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Satoshi tasked Finnish developer and early Bitcoin contributor Martti Malmi with creating content for the bitcoin.org website.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Blockchain analysts estimate that Nakamoto had mined about one million bitcoins before he disappeared in 2010 and handed the network alert key and control of the code repository over to Gavin Andresen.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Andresen later became lead developer at the Bitcoin Foundation, an organization founded in September 2012 to promote bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] After early "proof-of-concept" transactions, the first major users of bitcoin were black markets, such as the dark web Silk Road.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] During its 30 months of existence, beginning in February 2011, Silk Road exclusively accepted bitcoins as payment, transacting ₿9.9 million, worth about $214 million.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In May 2013, US authorities seized the unregistered exchange Mt.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In June 2013, the US Drug Enforcement Administration seized ₿11.02 from an individual attempting to use them to purchase illicit drugs.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This marked the first time a government agency had seized bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The FBI seized about ₿30,000 in October 2013 from Silk Road, following the arrest of its founder Ross Ulbricht.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In December 2013, the People's Bank of China prohibited Chinese financial institutions from using bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] After the announcement, the value of bitcoin dropped, and Baidu no longer accepted bitcoins for certain services.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Buying real-world goods with any virtual currency had been illegal in China since at least 2009.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Research produced by the University of Cambridge estimated that in 2017, there were 2.9 to 5.8 million unique users using a cryptocurrency wallet, most of them using bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In August 2017, the SegWit software upgrade was activated.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Segwit was intended to support the Lightning Network as well as improve scalability.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] SegWit opponents, who supported larger blocks as a scalability solution, forked to create Bitcoin Cash, one of many forks of bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In December 2017, the first futures on bitcoin was introduced by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME).
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In February 2018, the price crashed after China imposed a complete ban on bitcoin trading.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The percentage of bitcoin trading in the Chinese renminbi fell from over 90% in September 2017 to less than 1% in June 2018.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] During the same year, bitcoin prices were negatively affected by several hacks or thefts from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2020, some major companies and institutions started to acquire bitcoin: MicroStrategy invested $250 million in bitcoin as a treasury reserve asset, Square, Inc., $50 million, and MassMutual, $100 million.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In November 2020, PayPal added support for bitcoin in the US.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In February 2021, bitcoin's market capitalization reached $1 trillion for the first time.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In November 2021, the Taproot soft-fork upgrade was activated, adding support for Schnorr signatures, improved functionality of smart contracts and Lightning Network.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Before, bitcoin only used a custom elliptic curve with the ECDSA algorithm to produce signatures.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In September 2021, bitcoin became legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In October 2021, the first bitcoin futures exchange-traded fund (ETF), called BITO, from ProShares was approved by the SEC and listed on the CME.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In early 2022, during the Canadian trucker protests opposing COVID-19 vaccine mandates, organizers turned to bitcoin to receive donations after traditional financial platforms restricted access to funding.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Proponents highlighted bitcoin's use as a tool for fundraising in situations where access to conventional financial systems may be restricted.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In May and June 2022, the bitcoin price fell following the collapses of TerraUSD, a stablecoin, and the Celsius Network, a cryptocurrency loan company.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2023, ordinals—non-fungible tokens (NFTs)—on bitcoin, went live.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of June 2023, River Financial estimated that bitcoin had 81.7 million users, about 1% of the global population.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In January 2024, the first 11 US spot bitcoin ETFs began trading, offering direct exposure to bitcoin for the first time on American stock exchanges.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In December 2024, bitcoin price reached $100,000 for the first time, as US president-elect Donald Trump promised to make the US the "crypto capital of the planet" and to stockpile bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The same month, BlackRock, the world's largest asset manager, recommended investors to allocate up to 2% of their portfolio to bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of 2025, the Salvadoran government continues to describe Bitcoin as legal tender under the 2021 Bitcoin Law; however, a January 2025 reform removed obligations for businesses and the government to accept it, so many analysts regard its legal-tender status as effectively ended in practice.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In March 2025, President Trump signed an executive order to establish a strategic bitcoin reserve.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Later that year, some U.S. states, such as Texas and New Hampshire also instituted strategic bitcoin reserves, and the Czech National Bank bought less than €1 million in a "test portfolio".
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin logos made by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2009 (left) and 2010 (right).
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The unit of account of the bitcoin system is the *bitcoin*.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] It is most commonly represented with the symbol ₿ designed in 2010 and the currency code BTC.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] However, the BTC code does not conform to ISO 4217 as BT is the country code of Bhutan, and ISO 4217 requires the first letter used in global commodities to be 'X'.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] XBT, a code that conforms to ISO 4217 though not officially part of it, is used by Bloomberg L.P.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] No uniform capitalization convention exists; some sources use *Bitcoin*, capitalized, to refer to the technology and network, and *bitcoin*, lowercase, for the unit of account.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The *Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary* and the *Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary* use the capitalized and lowercase variants without distinction.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] One bitcoin is divisible to eight decimal places.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Units for smaller amounts of bitcoin are the millibitcoin (mBTC), equal to 1⁄1000 bitcoin, and the satoshi (sat), representing 1⁄100000000 (one hundred millionth) bitcoin, the smallest amount possible.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As a decentralized system, bitcoin operates without a central authority or single administrator, so that anyone can create a new bitcoin address and transact without needing any approval.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This is accomplished through a specialized distributed ledger called a *blockchain* that records bitcoin transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The blockchain is implemented as an ordered list of *blocks*.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Each block contains a SHA-256 hash of the previous block, chaining them in chronological order.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The blockchain is maintained by a peer-to-peer network.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Individual blocks, public addresses, and transactions within blocks are public information, and can be examined using a blockchain explorer.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nodes validate and broadcast transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Each node maintains a copy of the blockchain for ownership verification.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] A new block is created every 10 minutes on average, updating the blockchain across all nodes without central oversight.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This process tracks bitcoin spending, ensuring each bitcoin is spent only once.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Unlike a traditional ledger that tracks physical currency, bitcoins exist digitally as unspent outputs of transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In the blockchain, bitcoins are linked to specific strings called addresses.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Most often, an address encodes a hash of a single public key.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Creating such an address involves generating a random private key and then computing the corresponding address.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This process is almost instant, but the reverse (finding the private key for a given address) is nearly impossible.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Publishing such a bitcoin address does not risk its private key, and it is extremely unlikely to accidentally generate a used key with funds.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] To use bitcoins, owners need their private key to digitally sign transactions, which are verified by the network using the public key, keeping the private key secret.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] An address may encode the hash of a bitcoin script that specifies more complex requirements to spend the funds.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] One common example is "multisig", in which multiple distinct private keys must mutually sign any transaction that attempts to spend the funds.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin transactions use a Forth-like scripting language, involving one or more inputs and outputs.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] When sending bitcoins, a user specifies the recipients' addresses and the amount for each output.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This allows sending bitcoins to several recipients in a single transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] To prevent double-spending, each input must refer to a previous unspent output in the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Using multiple inputs is similar to using multiple coins in a cash transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As in a cash transaction, the sum of inputs can exceed the intended sum of payments.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In such a case, an additional output can return the change back to the payer.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Unallocated input satoshis in the transaction become the transaction fee.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Losing a private key means losing access to the bitcoins, with no other proof of ownership accepted by the protocol.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] For instance, in 2013, a user lost ₿7,500, valued at US$7.5 million, by accidentally discarding a hard drive with the private key.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] It is estimated that around 20% of all bitcoins are lost.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The private key must also be kept secret as its exposure, such as through a data breach, can lead to theft of the associated bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of December 2017, approximately ₿980,000 had been stolen from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Miners don't directly act as nodes, but do communicate with nodes.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The mining process in bitcoin involves maintaining the blockchain through computer processing power.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Miners group and broadcast new transactions into blocks, which are then verified by the network.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Each block must contain a proof of work (PoW) to be accepted, involving finding a nonce number that, combined with the block content, produces a hash numerically smaller than the network's *difficulty target*.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This PoW is simple to verify but hard to generate, requiring many attempts.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] PoW forms the basis of bitcoin's consensus mechanism.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The difficulty of generating a block is deterministically adjusted based on the mining power on the network by changing the difficulty target, which is recalibrated every 2,016 blocks (approximately two weeks) to maintain an average time of ten minutes between new blocks.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The process requires significant computational power and specialized hardware.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Miners who successfully create a new block with a valid nonce can collect transaction fees from the included transactions and a fixed reward in bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] To claim this reward, a special transaction called a *coinbase* is included in the block, with the miner as the payee.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] All bitcoins in existence have been created through this type of transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This reward is halved every 210,000 blocks until ₿21 million have been issued in total, which is expected to occur around the year 2140.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Afterward, miners will only earn from transaction fees.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] These fees are determined by the transaction's size and the amount of data stored, measured in satoshis per byte.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The proof of work system and the chaining of blocks make blockchain modifications very difficult, as altering one block requires changing all subsequent blocks.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As more blocks are added, modifying older blocks becomes increasingly challenging.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In case of disagreement, nodes trust the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] To tamper or censor the ledger, one needs to control the majority of the global hashrate.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The high cost required to reach this level of computational power secures the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The environmental impact of bitcoin mining is controversial and has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to restrictions or incentives in various jurisdictions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of 2025, a non-peer-reviewed study by the Cambridge Centre for Alternative Finance (CCAF) estimated that bitcoin mining represented 0.5% of global electricity consumption and 0.08% of world greenhouse gas emissions, comparable to Slovakia's emissions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] About half of the electricity used is generated through fossil fuels.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Moreover, mining hardware's short lifespan results in electronic waste.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In October 2025, the US was the largest mining country with 38% of the global bitcoin mining market share, followed by Russia (16%) and China (14%, despite all cryptocurrency trading and mining being banned there in 2021).
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, with funds linked to addresses, not real-world identities.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] While the owners of these addresses are not directly identified, all transactions are public on the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Patterns of use, like spending coins from multiple inputs, can hint at a common owner.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Public data can sometimes be matched with known address owners.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin exchanges might also need to collect personal data as per legal requirements.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] For enhanced privacy, users can generate a new address for each transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In the bitcoin network, each bitcoin is treated equally, ensuring basic fungibility.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] However, users and applications can choose to differentiate between bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] While wallets and software treat all bitcoins the same, each bitcoin's transaction history is recorded on the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This public record allows for chain analysis, where users can identify and potentially reject bitcoins from controversial sources.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Gox froze accounts containing bitcoins identified as stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin wallets were the first cryptocurrency wallets, enabling users to store the information necessary to transact bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in 2009 by Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin Core is among the best known clients.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist such as Bitcoin Unlimited.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Wallets can be full clients, with a full copy of the blockchain to check the validity of mined blocks, or lightweight clients, just to send and receive transactions without a local copy of the entire blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Third-party internet services, called online wallets or hot wallets, store users' credentials on their servers, making them susceptible of hacks.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Cold storage protects bitcoins from such hacks by keeping private keys offline, either through specialized hardware wallets or paper printouts.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nakamoto limited the block size to one megabyte.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The limited block size and frequency can lead to delayed processing of transactions, increased fees and a bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The Lightning Network, a second-layer routing network, is a potential scaling solution.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Research shows a trend towards centralization in bitcoin as miners join pools for stable income.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] If a single miner or pool controls more than 50% of the hashing power, it would allow them to censor transactions and double-spend coins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2014, mining pool Ghash.io reached 51% mining power, causing safety concerns, but later voluntarily capped its power at 39.99% for the benefit of the whole network.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] A few entities also dominate other parts of the ecosystem such as the client software, online wallets, and simplified payment verification (SPV) clients.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Sociologist Nigel Dodd argues that the essence of the bitcoin ideology is to remove money from social, as well as governmental, control.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] *The Economist* describes bitcoin as "a techno-anarchist project to create an online version of cash, a way for people to transact without the possibility of interference from malicious governments or banks".
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] These philosophical ideas initially attracted libertarians and anarchists.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Money serves three purposes: a store of value, a medium of exchange, and a unit of account.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to *The Economist* in 2014, bitcoin functions best as a medium of exchange.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2015, *The Economist* noted that bitcoins had three qualities useful in a currency: they are "hard to earn, limited in supply and easy to verify".
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] However, a 2018 assessment by *The Economist* stated that cryptocurrencies met none of these three criteria.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Per some researchers, as of 2015, bitcoin functions more as a payment system than as a currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Shiller wrote that bitcoin has potential as a unit of account for measuring the relative value of goods, as with Chile's Unidad de Fomento, but that "Bitcoin in its present form... doesn't really solve any sensible economic problem".
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The legal status of bitcoin varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Because of its decentralized nature and its global presence, regulating bitcoin is difficult.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] However, the use of bitcoin can be criminalized, and shutting down exchanges and the peer-to-peer economy in a given country would constitute a de facto ban.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The use of bitcoin by criminals has attracted the attention of financial regulators, legislative bodies, and law enforcement.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Nobel-prize winning economist Joseph Stiglitz says that bitcoin's anonymity encourages money laundering and other crimes.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] This is the main justification behind bitcoin bans.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of November 2021, nine countries applied an absolute ban (Algeria, Bangladesh, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, Qatar, and Tunisia) while another 42 countries had an implicit ban.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to Harvard Professor Kenneth Rogoff as of 2025, bitcoin is rarely used in regular transactions with merchants, but is popular in the informal economy and for criminal activities.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Prices are not usually quoted in bitcoin and trades involve conversions into fiat currencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Commonly cited reasons for not using bitcoin include high costs, the inability to process chargebacks, high price volatility, long transaction times, and transaction fees (especially for small purchases).
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] *Bloomberg* reported that bitcoin was being used for large-item purchases on the site Overstock.com and for cross-border payments to freelancers.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of 2015, there was little sign of bitcoin use in international remittances despite high fees charged by banks and Western Union.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] From September 2021 until January 2025, the Bitcoin Law made bitcoin a legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The adoption had been criticized internationally and within El Salvador.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2022, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) urged El Salvador to reverse its decision.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of 2022, the use of Bitcoin in El Salvador remained low: 80% of businesses refused to accept it.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2025, El Salvador's government revoked bitcoin's status as legal tender currency in order to comply with conditions set by the IMF for a loan.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] El Salvador still describes bitcoin as "legal tender", but its acceptance is no longer obligitory (as it is with the US dollar) and the El Salvador government no longer accepts bitcoin for payment of taxes or fees.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In April 2022, the Central African Republic (CAR) adopted bitcoin as legal tender alongside the CFA franc, but repealed the reform one year later.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin is also used by some governments.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] For instance, the Iranian government initially opposed cryptocurrencies, but later began using them to circumvent sanctions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Since 2020, Iran has required local bitcoin miners to sell bitcoin to the Central Bank of Iran, allowing the central bank to use it for imports.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Some constituent states and local governments also accept tax payments in bitcoin, including Colorado in the US and Zug and Lugano in Switzerland.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of 2023, the US government owned more than $5 billion worth of seized bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of 2018, the overwhelming majority of bitcoin transactions took place on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Since 2014, regulated bitcoin funds also allow exposure to the asset or to futures as an investment.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin is used as a store of value: individuals and companies such as the Winklevoss twins and Elon Musk's companies SpaceX and Tesla have each bought and sold hundreds of millions of dollars worth of bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin wealth is highly concentrated, with 0.01% holding 27% of in-circulation currency, as of 2021.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] As of March 2025, El Salvador had $550 million worth of bitcoin in its international reserves, about 6,102 coins.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin, along with other cryptocurrencies, has been described as an economic bubble by several economists, including Nobel Prize in Economics laureates, such as Joseph Stiglitz, James Heckman, and Paul Krugman.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Another recipient of the prize, Robert Shiller, argues that bitcoin is rather a fad that may become an asset class.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] He describes its price growth as an "epidemic", driven by contagious narratives.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2024, Jean Tirole, also Nobel laureate, described bitcoin as a "pure bubble" as its intrinsic value is zero.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to him, some bubbles are long-lasting such as gold and fiat currencies, and it is impossible to predict whether bitcoin would implode like other financial bubbles or become an alternative to gold.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The same year, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell described bitcoin as a digital competitor to gold but not to the dollar as he argued it is a highly volatile speculative asset not used as a form of payment.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2025, Kenneth Rogoff claimed that Krugman was wrong and that Bitcoin had value as it is competing with the dollar to become the means of exchange of the underground economy which represents 20% of the world's GDP.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to Rogoff, bitcoin is "the ideal currency for a more fragmented and uncertain global landscape" and it could become appealing to emerging-market central banks as a "politically neutral" reserve currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to research published in the *International Review of Financial Analysis* in 2018, bitcoin as an asset is highly volatile and does not behave like any other conventional asset.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] According to one 2022 analysis published in *The Journal of Alternative Investments*, bitcoin was less volatile than oil, silver, US Treasuries, and 190 stocks in the S&P 500 during and after the 2020 stock market crash.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The term *hodl* was created in December 2013 for holding bitcoin rather than selling it during periods of volatility.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] In 2014, economist Nouriel Roubini described bitcoin as a Ponzi scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Legal scholar Eric Posner disagrees, however, as "a real Ponzi scheme takes fraud; bitcoin, by contrast, seems more like a collective delusion".
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] A 2014 World Bank report also concluded that bitcoin was not a deliberate Ponzi scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin markets operate 24 hours a day, seven days a week, contrasting with traditional financial markets that have fixed trading hours.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] Bitcoin prices show much higher volatility and respond strongly to both regulatory changes and market events.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The volume of bitcoin trading can fluctuate considerably among various exchanges and geographic regions.
[src:cryptocurrency/bitcoin] The daily transaction volume of bitcoin across all exchanges typically reaches $50 billion as of 2025.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Cryptocurrencies are digital assets transferred on distributed ledgers without a central administrator.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Transfers are borderless, typically irreversible, and control depends on possession of private keys rather than accounts held by a single intermediary.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Criminals use cryptocurrencies when they make certain offences easier than traditional methods.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] For example, to move funds quickly across borders, take payment without going through banks, or launder proceeds through lightly regulated services.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] These traits suit offences such as theft, investment fraud and "pig-butchering," ransomware payments, darknet-market trade, money laundering and sanctions evasion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Since 2019, authorities have tried to limit the criminal misuse of crypto by bringing "virtual assets" and virtual-asset service providers (VASPs) into anti-money-laundering and counter-terrorist-financing (AML/CFT) rules.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The standards require licensing or registration, customer due diligence, and the "travel rule" for originator/beneficiary information.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Governments pair these with supervision and enforcement (including asset seizures, sanctions, and joint takedowns) and with more cross-border information-sharing among financial-intelligence units and police.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] However, offenders still work around these controls.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The overall scale of crypto-related crime is difficult to measure and figures below are not directly comparable (different geographies, methodologies, and crime types).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Still, recent indicators give a sense of order of magnitude.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Most exit scams (or *rugpulls*) as well as many ponzi schemes involving cryptocurrencies are performed through Initial Coin Offerings (ICOs).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] As an example, according to a report by Satis Group, almost 80% of all projects launched through an ICO in 2017 were scams.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] These scams usually involve attracting investments from mostly retail investors, inflating the price and the perpetrators subsequently abandoning the project in question after selling off their own shares.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The novelty of ICOs accounts for the current lack of governmental regulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] This lack of regulatory measures as well as the pseudonymity of cryptocurrency transactions and their international nature across countless jurisdictions in many different countries can make it much more difficult to identify and take legal action against perpetrators involved in these scams.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Since 2017 the SEC has been actively pursuing groups and individuals responsible for ICO-related scams.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Ponzi schemes are another common form of utilizing blockchain-based technologies to commit fraud.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Most schemes of this sort use multi-level marketing schemes to encourage investors to conduct risky investments.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Onecoin is one of the more notable examples of cryptocurrency-ponzi schemes: Founded in 2014 by Ruja Ignatova, OneCoin is estimated to have generated US$4 billion in income.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] While at least in China some of the investors' funds have been recovered and several members of the organisation arrested in the U.S., Ignatova herself is still at large.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Due to the inability of third parties to de-pseudonymize crypto transactions criminal entities have often resorted to using cryptocurrency to conduct money laundering.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Especially ICOs lacking KYC guidelines and anti-money laundering procedures are often used to launder illicit funds due to the pseudonymity they offer.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] By using ICOs criminals launder these funds by buying tokens off of legitimate investors and selling them.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] This issue is intensified by the lack of measures against money laundering implemented by centralized cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A well-known early example of money laundering using cryptocurrencies is Silk Road.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Shut down in 2013 with its founder Ross Ulbricht indicted for among other counts a money laundering conspiracy, the website was used for several illicit activities including money laundering solely using Bitcoin as a form of payment.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Apart from traditional cryptocurrencies, Non-Fungible Tokens (NFTs) are also commonly used in connection with money laundering activities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] NFTs are often used to perform Wash Trading by creating several different wallets for one individual, generating several fictitious sales and consequently selling the respective NFT to a third party.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] According to a report by Chainalysis, these types of wash trades are becoming increasingly popular among money launderers especially due to the largely anonymous nature of transactions on NFT marketplaces.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Auction platforms for NFT sales may face regulatory pressure to comply with anti-money laundering legislation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Canada is generally regarded as the first state actor implementing regulatory measures dealing with money laundering conducted by the usage of cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] By 2013 the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) — in direct reference to the centralized exchange Mt.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Gox — issued regulations making it clear that all crypto-to-fiat exchangers had to apply KYC- as well as anti-money laundering methods.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Any suspicious transactions have therefore to be reported to the authorities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Centralized exchanges have to register as money transmitters, with the exact definition of who and what constitutes a *money transmitter* in the crypto sphere being somewhat blurred and regulations differing between the different states of the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] An important exemption from these regulations is decentralized exchanges due to the fact that they do not hold any fiat currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] As part of the *Fifth Anti-Money Laundering Directive* of 2018 and in an effort to combat money laundering and the financing of terrorism, the European Union has issued a directive making all member-states have to make sure that crypto exchanges are licensed and registered.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The EU is furthermore planning to take measures to ensure that all customers of cryptocurrency exchanges are to verify their identity as part of the registration process.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Several NFT exchanges were labeled as virtual asset service providers that may be subject to Financial Crimes Enforcement Network regulations.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The European Union has yet to establish specific regulations to combat money laundering through NFTs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The European Commission announced in July 2022 that it is planning to draw regulations regarding that issue by 2024.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A cryptocurrency giveaway scam involves scammers compromising or impersonating celebrities, influencers, or well-known companies to falsely claim they are multiplying cryptocurrency or giving away free cryptocurrency via airdrop.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A variety of methods are used to promote these scams, primarily through posts and livestreams on social media.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] YouTube is a platform commonly used to promote this scam.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Popular accounts are hacked to stream pre-recorded videos of the impersonated figure, overlaid with fake giveaway announcements that often encourage viewers to visit the scammer's website.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In July 2020, Apple co-founder Steve Wozniak and 17 other victims filed a lawsuit against YouTube and its parent company, Google, alleging that the platform allowed scammers to use their name, image and likeness in cryptocurrency giveaway scams.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] After earlier dismissals based on Section 230, a 2024 California Court of Appeal ruling allowed the case to proceed, finding that YouTube's role may fall outside those legal protections, with the case now pending further proceedings in the lower court.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In the 2020 Twitter account hijacking, 130 high-profile accounts, including those of multi-billionaire Elon Musk and then U.S. president Joe Biden, were used to promote a bitcoin giveaway scam.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Within minutes of the initial tweets, more than 320 transactions had been sent to one of the wallet addresses, and over US$110,000 worth of bitcoin had been deposited before the scam messages were removed by Twitter.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Coinbase blacklisted the bitcoin address and said they stopped over 1,000 transactions totaling over US$280,000 from being sent.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Paper wallet generators allow users to create a wallet address and corresponding private key.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] While not dubious in itself, fraudsters can create infected generators that secretly communicate the generated keys to the creator, giving them control of the wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In August 2017, a bad actor began advertising an online IOTA wallet seed generator.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] To gain the victim's trust, they linked to a legitimate GitHub repository, claiming that their website used the same code.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In reality, the website used an intentionally predictable random number generator, resulting in the same IOTA wallet seeds being generated.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] On January 19, 2018, the attacker drained approximately US$3.94 million from wallets created during the six-month period.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Profiles associated with the website on GitHub, Reddit, and Quora that had provided support to users were deleted, and the website was updated to display the message: "Taken down.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Apologies." In January 2019, Europol arrested a 36-year-old man from Oxford, England believed to be behind the attack.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A pig-butchering scam is a form of online relationship and investment fraud in which perpetrators cultivate fake romantic or social relationships with victims before persuading them to invest money, often in fraudulent cryptocurrency schemes.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Law enforcement agencies have increasingly referred to the practice as romance baiting.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Such scams are commonplace on social media and dating apps, and often involve elements of catfishing, investment fraud, and romance scams.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In February 2014, the Pony virus, which spread to between 100,000 and 200,000 computers through a botnet, was reported to have stolen up to US$220,000 in cryptocurrency from 85 wallets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Researchers later discovered updated versions with the ability to steal 30 types of cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A type of Mac malware active in August 2013, Bitvanity posed as a vanity wallet address generator and stole addresses and private keys from other bitcoin client software.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A different trojan for macOS, called CoinThief was reported in February 2014 to be responsible for multiple bitcoin thefts.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The software was hidden in versions of some cryptocurrency apps on Download.com and MacUpdate.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A stealer, also known as a drainer or infostealer, is a type of malware designed to steal private information including private keys from cryptocurrency wallets, enabling attackers to access and transfer the funds to their wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The most common infections scan computers for wallet files and upload them to a remote server, where they can be cracked.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Many stealers also incorporate keyloggers to record keystrokes, often bypassing the need to crack the keys.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Clipboard hijacking involves a malware that detects when a cryptocurrency address is copied to the clipboard, and quickly replacing it to trick victims into sending their cryptocurrency to the attackers address.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The method is effective due to the difficulty of memorizing or manually typing wallet addresses, combined with the irreversible nature of cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Cryptocurrency is considered to be the "near-universal form of payment" for ransomware, a type of malware that encrypts a victim's data until a ransom is paid.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Ransomware attacks are estimated to have generated US$1.1 billion in 2019, US$999 million in 2020, a record US$1.25 billion in 2023, and US$813 million in 2024.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2024, a record breaking US$75 million ransom was paid to the Dark Angels ransomware group by an undisclosed Fortune 500 company.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Cryptojacking is the act of exploiting a computer to mine cryptocurrencies, often through websites, against the user's will or while the user is unaware.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] One notable piece of software used for cryptojacking was Coinhive, which was used in over two-thirds of cryptojacks before its March 2019 shutdown.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The cryptocurrencies mined the most often are privacy coins—coins with hidden transaction histories—such as Monero and Zcash.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Like most malicious attacks on the computing public, the motive is profit, but unlike other threats, it is designed to remain completely hidden from the user.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Cryptojacking malware can lead to slowdowns and crashes due to straining of computational resources.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Bitcoin mining by personal computers infected with malware is being challenged by dedicated hardware, such as FPGA and ASIC platforms, which are more efficient in terms of power consumption and thus may have lower costs than theft of computing resources.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Some mainstream news outlets have described cases in which kidnappers have targeted cryptocurrency holders in order to compel them to turn over access to their digital wallets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] According to reporting citing data from blockchain analysis firm Chainalysis, more than 30 such incidents were recorded in 2025, though the firm noted that many crimes may go unreported.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] One widely reported case involved a cryptocurrency investor who escaped from an apartment in Manhattan after allegedly being held captive for weeks, during which he was beaten and threatened with death in an attempt to force the transfer of digital assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Electricity theft associated with proof-of-work cryptocurrency mining has been reported in multiple countries, with operators illegally bypassing or tampering with meters and power lines to reduce operating costs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In Malaysia, Reuters reported that the national utility Tenaga Nasional Bhd estimated electricity losses of about 4.6 billion ringgit (US$1.11 billion) from power theft linked to illegal cryptocurrency mining between 2020 and August 2025, citing a parliamentary reply from the energy ministry.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Fraud factories in Asia traffic workers to scam Westerners into buying cryptocurrencies online.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Law-enforcement agencies and financial-intelligence units report using public-blockchain records to trace illicit flows, identify counterparties at service providers, and recover assets through seizure and forfeiture.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In recent operations, tracing supported large seizures linked to investment-fraud schemes; seized assets are typically managed and disposed of by custodial authorities such as the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Regulators and standard-setters note that FATF Recommendation 15 and related guidance shape cooperation with virtual-asset service providers, while also acknowledging barriers from privacy-enhancing techniques such as mixers and privacy coins.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] U.S. oversight bodies have likewise highlighted both the promise of on-chain transparency and persistent challenges in sanctions and AML enforcement.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2018, around US$1.7 billion in cryptocurrency was lost to scams, theft and fraud.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In the first quarter of 2019, such losses rose to US$1.2 billion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] 2022 was a record year for cryptocurrency theft, according to Chainalysis, with US$3.8 billion stolen worldwide during 125 system hacks, including US$1.7 billion stolen by "North Korea-linked hackers".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The *Parity Wallet* has had two security incidents amounting to 666,773 ETH lost or stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In July 2017, due to a bug in the multi-signature code, 153,037 ETH (approximately US$32 million at the time) were stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In November 2017, a subsequent multisignature flaw in *Parity* made 513,774 ETH (about US$150 million) unreachable; as of March 2019, the funds were still frozen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] There have been many cases of bitcoin theft.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] As of December 2017, around 980,000 bitcoins—over five percent of all bitcoin in circulation—had been lost on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] One type of theft involves a third party accessing the private key to a victim's bitcoin address, or an online wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] If the private key is stolen, all the bitcoins from the compromised address can be transferred.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In that case, the network does not have any provisions to identify the thief, block further transactions of those stolen bitcoins, or return them to the legitimate owner.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Theft also occurs at sites where bitcoins are used to purchase illicit goods.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In late November 2013, an estimated US$100 million in bitcoins were allegedly stolen from the online illicit goods marketplace Sheep Marketplace, which immediately closed.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Users tracked the coins as they were processed and converted to cash, but no funds were recovered and no culprits were identified.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A different black market, Silk Road 2, stated that during a February 2014 hack, bitcoins valued at $2.7 million were taken from escrow accounts.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Sites where users exchange bitcoins for cash or store them in "wallets" are also targets for theft.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Inputs.io, an Australian wallet service, was hacked twice in October 2013 and lost more than $1 million in bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] GBL, a Chinese bitcoin trading platform, suddenly shut down on 26 October 2013; subscribers, unable to log in, lost up to $5 million worth of bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Gox, one of the largest virtual currency exchanges, filed for bankruptcy in Tokyo amid reports that bitcoins worth US$350 million had been stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Flexcoin, a bitcoin storage specialist based in Alberta, Canada, shut down in March 2014 after saying it discovered a theft of about $650,000 in bitcoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Poloniex, a digital currency exchange, reported in March 2014 that it lost bitcoins valued at around $50,000.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In January 2015 UK-based bitstamp, the third busiest bitcoin exchange globally was hacked and US$5 million in bitcoins were stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In February 2015, a Chinese exchange named BTER lost bitcoins worth nearly $2 million to hackers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] A major bitcoin exchange, Bitfinex, was compromised by the 2016 Bitfinex hack, when nearly 120,000 bitcoins (around US$71 million) were stolen in 2016.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Bitfinex was forced to suspend its trading.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The theft was the second-largest bitcoin heist ever, dwarfed only by the Mt.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] According to *Forbes*, "All of Bitfinex's customers... will stand to lose money.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The company has announced a cut of 36.067% across the board." Following the hack the company failed to refund customers, though efforts are continuing.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2022, the US government recovered 94,636 bitcoin (worth approximately $3.6 billion at the time of recovery) from the 2016 thefts of the Bitfinex exchange, reported as the "largest financial seizure" in U.S. history.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] By February 2022, the amount of bitcoin stolen in 2016 had increased in value to $4.5 billion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Two people were arrested for the thefts in 2022; married couple Ilya "Dutch" Lichtenstein and rapper Heather "Razzlekhan" Morgan were charged with conspiracy to commit money laundering and conspiracy to defraud the United States.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] On May 7, 2019, hackers stole over 7000 Bitcoins from the Binance Cryptocurrency Exchange, at a value of over 40 million US dollars.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Binance CEO Zhao Changpeng stated: "The hackers used a variety of techniques, including phishing, viruses, and other attacks...
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Charles Hayter, founder of the digital currency comparison website CryptoCompare said, "It's a reminder of the fragility of the infrastructure in such a nascent industry." According to the hearing of the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Japan and the United States have accused North Korean hackers of stealing cryptocurrency worth over $300 million from the Japan-based exchange DMM Bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The theft was attributed to the TraderTraitor group, believed to be part of the Lazarus Group, which is allegedly linked to North Korean authorities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The incident occurred in late May 2024, involving the theft of 4,502.9 Bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The theft involved the hackers using social engineering tactics to impersonate a recruiter on LinkedIn and send a malicious pre-employment test to an employee at a crypto wallet software company.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] This allowed them to compromise the employee's system and manipulate a legitimate transaction request from DMM, resulting in the loss of 4,502.9 Bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The FBI and Japan's National Police Agency are collaborating to combat North Korea's cybercrime activities, which date back to the mid-1990s and include a cyber-warfare unit known as Bureau 121.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In June 2016, hackers exploited a vulnerability in The DAO to steal US$50 million.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Subsequently, the currency was forked into Ethereum Classic, and Ethereum, with the latter continuing with the new blockchain without the exploited translations.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] On November 21, 2017, Tether announced that it had been hacked, losing $31 million in USDT from its core treasury wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The company has 'tagged' the stolen currency, hoping to 'lock' them in the hacker's wallet (making them unspendable).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2022, hackers created a signature account on a blockchain bridge called "Wormhole" and stole more than $300 million worth of ether.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2015, two members of the Silk Road Task Force—a multi-agency federal task force that carried out the U.S. investigation of Silk Road—were convicted over charges pertaining to corruption.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Former DEA agent, Carl Mark Force, had attempted to extort Silk Road founder Ross Ulbricht ("Dread Pirate Roberts") by faking the murder of an informant.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] He pleaded guilty to money laundering, obstruction of justice, and extortion under color of official right, and was sentenced to 6.5 years in federal prison.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Secret Service agent, Shaun Bridges, pleaded guilty to crimes relating to his diversion of $800,000 worth of bitcoins to his personal account during the investigation, and also separately pleaded guilty to money laundering in connection to another cryptocurrency theft.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Bridges was sentenced to almost eight years in federal prison.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Gerald Cotten founded QuadrigaCX in 2013, after graduating from the Schulich School of Business in Toronto.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Cotten was acting as the sole curator of the exchange.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Quadriga had no official bank accounts since banks at the time had no method of managing cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In late 2018, Canada's largest crypto exchange QuadrigaCX lost US$190 million in cryptocurrency when the owner died; he was the only one with knowledge of the password to a storage wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The exchange filed for bankruptcy in 2019.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2018, Ellis Pinsky, 15 years old, was accused of orchestrating a scheme to steal millions of dollars' worth of cryptocurrencies from Michael Terpin, a prominent cryptocurrency investor.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The scheme involved a social engineering technique known as the SIM swap scam.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The case attracted significant attention due to Pinsky's young age and the substantial amount of money involved.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] It raised questions about the security of digital assets and the challenges in regulating and prosecuting crimes in the rapidly evolving world of cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Pinsky later reached a settlement to return $22 million in cryptocurrency to Terpin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In May 2020, Pinsky experienced a home invasion by intruders searching for remaining stolen assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Terpin also sued Nicholas Truglia and won a $75.8 million judgment against Truglia in 2019 in California state court.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] On July 15, 2020, Twitter accounts of prominent personalities and firms, including Joe Biden, Barack Obama, Bill Gates, Elon Musk, Jeff Bezos, Apple, Kanye West, Michael Bloomberg and Uber were hacked.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Twitter confirmed that it was a coordinated social engineering attack on their own employees.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Twitter released its statement six hours after the attack took place.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Hackers posted the message to transfer the Bitcoin to a Bitcoin wallet, which would double the amount.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The wallet's balance was expected to increase to more than $100,000 as the message spread among Twitter followers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2021, US Authorities carried out a raid on James Zhong's home in Gainesville, Georgia.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Authorities found over 51,000 bitcoin that Zhong had stolen from Silk Road between 2012 and 2013.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Through an error on Silk Road, Zhong was able to withdraw more bitcoin than what was initially deposited.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] He concealed his identity and was able to evade authorities for nearly a decade.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Zhong ended up pleading guilty to wire fraud and was sentenced to 1 year and 1 day in prison along with a forfeiture of all bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2022, the Federal Trade Commission reported that $139 million in cryptocurrency was stolen by romance scammers in 2020.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Some scammers target dating apps with fake profiles.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In early 2022, the Beanstalk cryptocurrency was stripped of its reserves, which were valued at more than US$180 million, after attackers had managed to use borrowed US$80 million in cryptocurrency to buy enough voting rights to transfer the reserves to their own accounts outside the system.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] It was initially unclear if such an exploit of governance procedures was illegal.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2025, A Nigerian scammer impersonated Trump ally Steve Witkoff by creating a nearly identical email address to solicit a $250,000 cryptocurrency donation from a political donor intended for the Trump-Vance Inaugural Committee.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The donor, deceived by the subtle change in the email domain, transferred 250,300 USDT.ETH, which was quickly laundered through multiple wallets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The FBI, with help from Tether and Binance, managed to recover and freeze about $40,300 of the stolen funds, but over $210,000 remains missing.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Officials warn that the complexity of blockchain transactions makes recovering stolen crypto extremely difficult.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Josh Garza, who founded the cryptocurrency startups GAW Miners and ZenMiner in 2014, acknowledged in a plea agreement that the companies were part of a pyramid scheme, and pleaded guilty to wire fraud in 2015.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Securities and Exchange Commission separately brought a civil enforcement action against Garza, who was eventually ordered to pay a judgment of US$9.1 million plus $700,000 in interest.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The SEC's complaint stated that Garza, through his companies, had fraudulently sold "investment contracts representing shares in the profits they claimed would be generated" from mining.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Garza was later found guilty of fraud and ordered to pay US$9 million and begin serving a 21-month sentence commencing January 2019 by the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Attorney's Office District of Connecticut.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] The cryptocurrency community refers to pre-mining, hidden launches, ICO or extreme rewards for the altcoin founders as deceptive practices.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] This is at times an inherent part of the cryptocurrency's design.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] Pre-mining refers to the practice of generating the currency before its released to the public.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] FTX and Alameda Research founder and CEO Sam Bankman-Fried was indicted by the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] District Court for the Southern District of New York in December 2022 and charged with commodities and wire fraud, securities fraud and money laundering, as well as with violating campaign finance laws.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-and-crime] In 2025, U.S. authorities led by the Department of Justice and the FBI's San Diego Field Office have seized approximately $2.5 million in cryptocurrency linked to a series of sophisticated fraud schemes.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Individual coin ownership records are stored in a digital ledger or blockchain, which is a computerized database that uses a consensus mechanism to secure transaction records, control the creation of additional coins, and verify the transfer of coin ownership.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The two most common consensus mechanisms are proof of work and proof of stake.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are generally viewed as a distinct asset class in practice.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1983, American cryptographer David Chaum conceived of a type of cryptographic electronic money called ecash.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Later, in 1995, he implemented it through Digicash, an early form of cryptographic electronic payments.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Digicash required user software in order to withdraw notes from a bank and designate specific encrypted keys before they could be sent to a recipient.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This allowed the digital currency to be untraceable by a third party.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1996, the National Security Agency published a paper entitled *How to Make a Mint: The Cryptography of Anonymous Electronic Cash*, describing a cryptocurrency system.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The paper was first published in an MIT mailing list (October 1996) and later (April 1997) in *The American Law Review*.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 1998, Wei Dai described "b-money," an anonymous, distributed electronic cash system.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Shortly thereafter, Nick Szabo described bit gold.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Like bitcoin and other later cryptocurrencies, bit gold was proposed as a digital currency system in which users would generate money by completing proof-of-work functions whose solutions were cryptographically chained and published.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In January 2009, bitcoin was created by pseudonymous developer Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] It used SHA-256, a cryptographic hash function, in its proof-of-work scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2011, Namecoin was created as an attempt at forming a decentralized DNS.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In October 2011, Litecoin was released, which used scrypt as its hash function instead of SHA-256.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Peercoin, created in August 2012, used a hybrid of proof-of-work and proof-of-stake.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency has undergone several periods of growth and retraction, including several bubbles and market crashes, such as in 2011, 2013–2014/15, 2017–2018, and 2021–2023.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2014, the UK announced its Treasury had commissioned a study of cryptocurrencies and what role, if any, they could play in the UK economy.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The study was also to report on whether regulation should be considered.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Its final report was published in 2018, and it issued a consultation on cryptoassets and stablecoins in January 2021.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, El Salvador became the first country to accept bitcoin as legal tender, after the Legislative Assembly had voted 62–22 to pass a bill submitted by President Nayib Bukele classifying the cryptocurrency as such.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In August 2021, Cuba followed with Resolution 215 to recognize and regulate cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the government of China, the single largest market for cryptocurrency, declared all cryptocurrency transactions illegal.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This completed a crackdown on cryptocurrency that had previously banned the operation of intermediaries and miners within China.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, the world's second largest cryptocurrency at that time, Ethereum, transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an upgrade process known as "the Merge".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] According to the Ethereum Founder, the upgrade would cut both Ethereum's energy use and carbon-dioxide emissions by 99.9%.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 11 November 2022, FTX Trading Ltd., a cryptocurrency exchange, which also operated a crypto hedge fund, and had been valued at $18 billion, filed for bankruptcy.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] An October 2024 survey from the Pew Research Center found that 63% of adults in the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] "have little to no confidence that current ways to invest in, trade or use cryptocurrencies are reliable and safe." The survey also reported that 17% of U.S. adults had directly interacted with cryptocurrency, which was statistically unchanged from 2021.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The word "cryptocurrency", in its modern sense, was added to the Oxford English Dictionary in September 2018, with its earliest usage noted as being on Twitter in September 2009; its diminutive, *crypto*, was entered in 2022.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018 *cryptocurrency* was added to the *Merriam-Webster Dictionary*.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] After the early innovation of bitcoin in 2008 and the early network effect gained by bitcoin, tokens, cryptocurrencies, and other digital assets that were not bitcoin became collectively known during the 2010s as alternative cryptocurrencies, or "**altcoins**".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Sometimes the term "alt coins" was used, or disparagingly, "**shitcoins**".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Paul Vigna of *The Wall Street Journal* described altcoins in 2020 as "alternative versions of Bitcoin" given its role as the model protocol for cryptocurrency designers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A Polytechnic University of Catalonia thesis in 2021 used a broader description, including not only alternative versions of bitcoin but every cryptocurrency other than bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] As of early 2020, there were more than 5,000 cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Altcoins often have underlying differences when compared to bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, Litecoin aims to process a block every 2.5 minutes, rather than bitcoin's 10 minutes which allows Litecoin to confirm transactions faster than bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Another example is Ethereum, which has smart contract functionality that allows decentralized applications to be run on its blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Ethereum was the most used blockchain in 2020, according to Bloomberg News.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2016, it had the largest "following" of any altcoin, according to the *New York Times*.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Significant market price rallies across multiple altcoin markets are often referred to as an "altseason".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Stablecoins are cryptocurrencies designed to maintain a stable level of purchasing power.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Notably, these designs are not foolproof, as a number of stablecoins have crashed or lost their peg.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, on 11 May 2022, Terra's stablecoin UST fell from $1 to 26 cents.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The subsequent failure of Terraform Labs resulted in the loss of nearly $40B invested in the Terra and Luna coins.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2022, South Korean prosecutors requested the issuance of an Interpol Red Notice against the company's founder, Do Kwon.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In Hong Kong, the expected regulatory framework for stablecoins in 2023/24 is being shaped and includes a few considerations.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] About 764,000 people who invested after the all time high on 19 January 2025 lost money.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The Melania meme coin experienced extreme volatility in its first days, after which it declined in price.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are a category of cryptocurrencies that originated from Internet memes or jokes.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] One example is Dogecoin, a memecoin featuring the Shiba Inu dog from the Doge meme.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Donald Trump and his wife Melania are the subject of their own meme coins, both of which declined in value soon after launch.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Memecoins are known for extreme volatility; for example, the record-high value for a Dogecoin was 73 cents, but that had plunged to 13 cents by mid-2024.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Physical cryptocurrency coins have been made as promotional items and some have become collectibles.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some of these have a private key embedded in them to access crypto worth a few dollars.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] There have also been attempts to issue bitcoin "bank notes".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The term "physical bitcoin" is used in the finance industry when investment funds that hold crypto purchased from crypto exchanges put their crypto holdings in a specialised bank called a "custodian".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] These physical representations of cryptocurrency do not hold any value by themselves; these are only utilized for collectable purposes.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, the first incarnation of the bitcoin Casascius, coins made of silver, brass or aluminum sometimes with gold plating, or Titan Bitcoin, which in silver or gold versions are sought after by numismatists.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The underlying technical system upon which cryptocurrencies are based was created by Satoshi Nakamoto.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Within a proof-of-work system such as bitcoin, the safety, integrity, and balance of ledgers are maintained by a community of mutually distrustful parties referred to as miners.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners use their computers to help validate and timestamp transactions, adding them to the ledger in accordance with a particular timestamping scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, transactions are validated by holders of the associated cryptocurrency, sometimes grouped together in stake pools.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called *blocks*, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A blockchain is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A "node" is a computer that connects to a cryptocurrency network.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The node supports the cryptocurrency's network through either relaying transactions, validation, or hosting a copy of the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In terms of relaying transactions, each network computer (node) has a copy of the blockchain of the cryptocurrency it supports.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] When a transaction is made, the node creating the transaction broadcasts details of the transaction using encryption to other nodes throughout the node network so that the transaction (and every other transaction) is known.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Node owners are either volunteers, those hosted by the organization or body developing the technology, or those incentivised by rewards from the node network.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove" the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The first timestamping scheme invented was the proof-of-work scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The most widely used proof-of-work schemes are based on SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some other hashing algorithms that are used for proof-of-work include CryptoNote, Blake, SHA-3, and X11.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Another method is called the proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-stake is a method of securing a cryptocurrency network and achieving distributed consensus through requesting users to show ownership of a certain amount of currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] It is different from proof-of-work systems that run difficult hashing algorithms to validate electronic transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The scheme is largely dependent on the coin, and there is currently no standard form of it.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies use a combined proof-of-work and proof-of-stake scheme.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On a blockchain, *mining* is the validation of transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For this effort, successful miners obtain new cryptocurrency as a reward.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The reward decreases transaction fees by creating a complementary incentive to contribute to the processing power of the network.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The rate of generating hashes, which validate any transaction, has been increased by the use of specialized hardware such as FPGAs and ASICs running complex hashing algorithms like SHA-256 and scrypt.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This arms race for cheaper-yet-efficient machines has existed since bitcoin was introduced in 2009.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Mining is measured by hash rate, typically in TH/s.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A 2023 IMF working paper found that crypto mining could generate 450 million tons of CO2 emissions by 2027, accounting for 0.7 percent of global emissions, or 1.2 percent of the world total.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] With more people entering the world of virtual currency, generating hashes for validation has become more complex over time, forcing miners to invest increasingly large sums of money to improve computing performance.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Consequently, the reward for finding a hash has diminished and often does not justify the investment in equipment and cooling facilities (to mitigate the heat the equipment produces) and the electricity required to run them.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular regions for mining include those with inexpensive electricity, a cold climate, and jurisdictions with clear and conducive regulations.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] By July 2019, bitcoin's electricity consumption was estimated to be approximately 7 gigawatts, around 0.2% of the global total, or equivalent to the energy consumed nationally by Switzerland.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some miners pool resources, sharing their processing power over a network to split the reward equally, according to the amount of work they contributed to the probability of finding a block.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A "share" is awarded to members of the mining pool who present a valid partial proof-of-work.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] As of February 2018, the Chinese government has halted trading of virtual currency, banned initial coin offerings, and shut down mining.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Many Chinese miners have since relocated to Canada and Texas.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] One company is operating data centers for mining operations at Canadian oil and gas field sites due to low gas prices.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2018, Hydro Quebec proposed to the provincial government to allocate 500 megawatts of power to crypto companies for mining.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] According to a February 2018 report from *Fortune*, Iceland has become a haven for cryptocurrency miners in part because of its cheap electricity.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2018, the city of Plattsburgh, New York put an 18-month moratorium on all cryptocurrency mining in an effort to preserve natural resources and the "character and direction" of the city.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, Kazakhstan became the second-biggest crypto-currency mining country, producing 18.1% of the global exahash rate.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The country built a compound containing 50,000 computers near Ekibastuz.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] An increase in cryptocurrency mining increased the demand for graphics cards (GPU) in 2017.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The computing power of GPUs makes them well-suited to generating hashes.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Popular favorites of cryptocurrency miners, such as Nvidia's GTX 1060 and GTX 1070 graphics cards, as well as AMD's RX 570 and RX 580 GPUs, doubled or tripled in price – or simply went out of stock.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A GTX 1070 Ti, which was released at a price of $450, sold for as much as $1,100.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Another popular card, the GTX 1060 (6 GB model), released at an MSRP of $250, sold for almost $500.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] RX 570 and RX 580 cards from AMD were out of stock for almost a year.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners regularly buy up the entire stock of new GPUs as soon as they are available.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Nvidia has asked retailers to do what they can when it comes to selling GPUs to gamers instead of miners.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Numerous companies developed dedicated crypto-mining accelerator chips, capable of price-performance far higher than that of CPU or GPU mining.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] At one point, Intel marketed its own brand of crypto accelerator chip, named Blockscale.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A cryptocurrency wallet is a means of storing the public and private "keys" (address) or seed, which can be used to receive or spend the cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] With the private key, it is possible to write in the public ledger, effectively spending the associated cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] With the public key, it is possible for others to send currency to the wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] There exist multiple methods of storing keys or seed in a wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, rather than anonymous; the cryptocurrency in a wallet is not tied to a person but rather to one or more specific keys (or "addresses").
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Thereby, bitcoin owners are not immediately identifiable, but all transactions are publicly available in the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Still, cryptocurrency exchanges are often required by law to collect the personal information of their users.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Monero, Zerocoin, Zerocash, and CryptoNote, implement additional measures to increase privacy, such as by using zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] A recent 2020 study presented different attacks on privacy in cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The attacks demonstrated how the anonymity techniques are not sufficient safeguards.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In order to improve privacy, researchers suggested several different ideas, including new cryptographic schemes and mechanisms for hiding the IP address of the source.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrencies are used primarily outside banking and governmental institutions and are exchanged over the Internet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof-of-work cryptocurrencies, such as bitcoin, offer block rewards incentives for miners.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] There has been an implicit belief that whether miners are paid by block rewards or transaction fees does not affect the security of the blockchain, but a study suggests that this may not be the case under certain circumstances.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The rewards paid to miners increase the supply of the cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] By making sure that verifying transactions is a costly business, the integrity of the network can be preserved as long as benevolent nodes control a majority of computing power.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The verification algorithm requires a lot of processing power, and thus electricity, in order to make verification costly enough to accurately validate the public blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Miners have to factor in the costs associated with expensive equipment necessary to stand a chance of solving a hash problem, and consider the significant amount of electrical power in search of the solution.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Generally, the block rewards outweigh electricity and equipment costs, but this may not always be the case.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The current value, not the long-term value, of the cryptocurrency supports the reward scheme to incentivize miners to engage in costly mining activities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2018, bitcoin's design caused a 1.4% welfare loss compared to an efficient cash system, while a cash system with 2% money growth has a minor 0.003% welfare cost.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The main source for this inefficiency is the large mining cost, which is estimated to be US$360 million per year.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This translates into users being willing to accept a cash system with an inflation rate of 230% before being better off using bitcoin as a means of payment.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] However, the efficiency of the bitcoin system can be significantly improved by optimizing the rate of coin creation and minimizing transaction fees.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Another potential improvement is to eliminate inefficient mining activities by changing the consensus protocol altogether.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Transaction fees (sometimes also referred to as *miner fees* or *gas fees*) for cryptocurrency depend mainly on the supply of network capacity at the time, versus the demand from the currency holder for a faster transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The ability for the holder to be allowed to set the fee manually often depends on the wallet software used, and central exchanges for cryptocurrency (CEX) usually do not allow the customer to set a custom transaction fee for the transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Their wallet software, such as Coinbase Wallet, however, might support adjusting the fee.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Select cryptocurrency exchanges have offered to let the user choose between different presets of transaction fee values during the currency conversion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] One of those exchanges, namely **LiteBit**, previously headquartered in the Netherlands, was forced to cease all operations in August 2023, "due to market changes and regulatory pressure".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The "recommended fee" suggested by the network will often depend on the time of day (due to depending on network load).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For Ethereum, transaction fees differ by computational complexity, bandwidth use, and storage needs, while bitcoin transaction fees differ by transaction size and whether the transaction uses SegWit.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the median transaction fee for Ether corresponded to $2.2845, while for bitcoin it corresponded to $0.659.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some cryptocurrencies have no transaction fees, the most well-known example being Nano (XNO), and instead rely on client-side proof-of-work as the transaction prioritization and anti-spam mechanism.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency exchanges allow customers to trade cryptocurrencies for other assets, such as conventional fiat money, or to trade between different digital currencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Crypto marketplaces do not guarantee that an investor is completing a purchase or trade at the optimal price.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] As a result, as of 2020, it was possible to arbitrage to find the difference in price across several markets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Atomic swaps are a mechanism where one cryptocurrency can be exchanged directly for another cryptocurrency without the need for a trusted third party, such as an exchange.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Jordan Kelley, founder of Robocoin, launched the first bitcoin ATM in the United States in February 2014.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The kiosk installed in Austin, Texas, is similar to bank ATMs but has scanners to read government-issued identification such as a driver's license, or a passport to confirm users' identities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] An initial coin offering (ICO) is a controversial means of raising funds for a new cryptocurrency venture.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] An ICO may be used by startups with the intention of avoiding regulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In an ICO campaign, a percentage of the cryptocurrency (usually in the form of "tokens") is sold to early backers of the project in exchange for legal tender or other cryptocurrencies, often bitcoin or Ether.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] According to PricewaterhouseCoopers, four of the 10 biggest proposed initial coin offerings have used Switzerland as a base, where they are frequently registered as non-profit foundations.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The market capitalization of a cryptocurrency is calculated by multiplying the price by the number of coins in circulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The total cryptocurrency market cap has historically been dominated by bitcoin accounting for at least 50% of the market cap value where altcoins have increased and decreased in market cap value in relation to bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's value is largely determined by speculation among other technological limiting factors known as blockchain rewards coded into the architecture technology of bitcoin itself.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The cryptocurrency market cap follows a trend known as the "halving", which is when the block rewards received from bitcoin are halved due to technological mandated limited factors instilled into bitcoin which in turn limits the supply of bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] As the date reaches near of a halving (twice thus far historically) the cryptocurrency market cap increases, followed by a downtrend.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] By June 2021, cryptocurrency had begun to be offered by some wealth managers in the US for 401(k)s.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cryptocurrency prices are much more volatile than established financial assets such as stocks.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For example, over one week in May 2022, bitcoin lost 20% of its value and Ethereum lost 26%, while Solana and Cardano lost 41% and 35% respectively.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The falls were attributed to warnings about inflation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] By comparison, in the same week, the Nasdaq tech stock index fell 7.6 per cent and the FTSE 100 was 3.6 per cent down.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In the longer term, of the 10 leading cryptocurrencies identified by the total value of coins in circulation in January 2018, only four (bitcoin, Ethereum, Cardano and Ripple (XRP)) were still in that position in early 2022.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The total value of all cryptocurrencies was $2 trillion at the end of 2021, but had halved nine months later.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* has commented that the crypto sector has become "intertwined" with the rest of the capital markets and "sensitive to the same forces that drive tech stocks and other risk assets," such as inflation forecasts.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] There are also *centralized* databases, outside of blockchains, that store crypto market data.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Compared to the blockchain, databases perform fast as there is no verification process.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Four of the most popular cryptocurrency market databases are CoinMarketCap, CoinGecko, BraveNewCoin, and Cryptocompare.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] According to Alan Feuer of *The New York Times*, libertarians and anarcho-capitalists were attracted to the philosophical idea behind bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Early bitcoin supporter Roger Ver said: "At first, almost everyone who got involved did so for philosophical reasons.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] We saw bitcoin as a great idea, as a way to separate money from the state." Economist Paul Krugman argues that cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are "something of a cult" based in "paranoid fantasies" of government power.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] David Golumbia says that the ideas influencing bitcoin advocates emerge from right-wing extremist movements such as the Liberty Lobby and the John Birch Society and their anti-Central Bank rhetoric, or, more recently, Ron Paul and Tea Party-style libertarianism.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Steve Bannon, who owns a "good stake" in bitcoin, sees cryptocurrency as a form of disruptive populism, taking control back from central authorities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Bitcoin's founder, Satoshi Nakamoto, supported the idea that cryptocurrencies go well with libertarianism.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] "It's very attractive to the libertarian viewpoint if we can explain it properly," Nakamoto said in 2008.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Monthly cryptocurrency transfers under $10,000 to and from Africa reached $316 million in June 2020, according to Chainalysis data.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies are unregulated in many countries and their legal status is unclear, meaning there is no safety net and little recourse for lost funds.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Some migrants in the United Arab Emirates used cryptocurrencies to send remittances home, claiming lower fees compared with traditional remittance services.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2025, some publicly traded companies announced plans to raise capital to buy and hold bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies as treasury assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Reuters reported that the inherent volatility of crypto tokens makes them a poor fit for boards with a low risk appetite, potentially limiting their appeal beyond core industry players.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The rise in the popularity of cryptocurrencies and their adoption by financial institutions has led some governments to assess whether regulation is needed to protect users.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) has defined cryptocurrency-related services as "virtual asset service providers" (VASPs) and recommended that they be regulated with the same money laundering (AML) and know your customer (KYC) requirements as financial institutions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2020, the Joint Working Group on interVASP Messaging Standards published "IVMS 101", a universal common language for communication of required originator and beneficiary information between VASPs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The FATF and financial regulators were informed as the data model was developed.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2020, FATF updated its guidance to include the "Travel Rule" for cryptocurrencies, a measure which mandates that VASPs obtain, hold, and exchange information about the originators and beneficiaries of virtual asset transfers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Subsequent standardized protocol specifications recommended using JSON for relaying data between VASPs and identity services.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] As of December 2020, the IVMS 101 data model has yet to be finalized and ratified by the three global standard setting bodies that created it.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The European Commission published a digital finance strategy in September 2020.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This included a draft regulation on Markets in Crypto-Assets (MiCA), which aimed to provide a comprehensive regulatory framework for digital assets in the EU.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In June 2021, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision proposed that banks that held cryptocurrency assets must set aside capital to cover all potential losses.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, if a bank were to hold bitcoin worth $2 billion, it would be required to set aside enough capital to cover the entire $2 billion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This is a more extreme standard than banks are usually held to when it comes to other assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] However, this is a proposal and not a regulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The IMF has sought seeking a coordinated, consistent and comprehensive approach to supervising cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Tobias Adrian, the IMF's financial counsellor and head of its monetary and capital markets department said in a January 2022 interview that "Agreeing global regulations is never quick.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In May 2024, 15 years after the advent of the first blockchain, bitcoin, the US Congress advanced a bill to the full House of Representatives to provide regulatory clarity for digital assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2017, China banned ICOs to cause abnormal return from cryptocurrency decreasing during announcement window.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The liquidity changes by banning ICOs in China was temporarily negative while the liquidity effect became positive after news.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 18 May 2021, China banned financial institutions and payment companies from being able to provide cryptocurrency transaction related services.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This led to a sharp fall in the price of the biggest proof of work cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] For instance, bitcoin fell 31%, Ethereum fell 44%, Binance Coin fell 32% and Dogecoin fell 30%.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Proof of work mining was the next focus, with regulators in popular mining regions citing the use of electricity generated from highly polluting sources such as coal to create bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In September 2021, the Chinese government declared all cryptocurrency transactions of any kind illegal, completing its crackdown on cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The proposed legislation was criticised by Cook Islands Crown Law's deputy solicitor general David Greig, who described it as "flawed" and said that some provisions were "clearly unconstitutional".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The Cook Islands Financial Services Development Authority described Drumcliffe's involvement as a conflict of interest.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Similar criticism was echoed by Auckland University of Technology cryptocurrency specialist and senior lecturer Jeff Nijsse and University of Otago political scientist Professor Robert Patman, who described it as government overreach and described it as inconsistent with international law.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Cook Islands Prime Minister Mark Brown defended the legislation as part of the territory's fight against international cybercrime.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 9 June 2021, El Salvador announced that it will adopt bitcoin as legal tender, becoming the first country to do so.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] As of 17 January 2025, the European Securities and Markets Authority (ESMA) issued guidance to crypto-asset service providers (CASPs) allowing them to maintain crypto-asset services for non-compliant ARTs and EMTs until the end of March 2025.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The rest of MiCA came into force as of 30 December 2024, covering crypto-assets other than ART and EMT and CASPs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] MiCA excludes crypto-assets if they qualify as financial instruments according to ESMA guidelines published on 17 December 2024 as well as crypto-assets that are unique and not fungible with other crypto-assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] At present, India neither prohibits nor allows investment in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2020, the Supreme Court of India had lifted the ban on cryptocurrency, which was imposed by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Since then, an investment in cryptocurrency is considered legitimate, though there is still ambiguity about the issues regarding the extent and payment of tax on the income accrued thereupon and also its regulatory regime.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] But it is being contemplated that the Indian Parliament will soon pass a specific law to either ban or regulate the cryptocurrency market in India.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] He mooted regulating the cryptocurrency market rather than completely banning it.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] He favoured following IMF and FATF guidelines in this regard.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] South Africa, which has seen a large number of scams related to cryptocurrency, is said to be putting a regulatory timeline in place that will produce a regulatory framework.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The largest scam occurred in April 2021, where the two founders of an African-based cryptocurrency exchange called Africrypt, Raees Cajee and Ameer Cajee, disappeared with $3.8 billion worth of bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Mirror Trading International disappeared with $170 million worth of cryptocurrency in January 2021.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In March 2021, South Korea implemented new legislation to strengthen their oversight of digital assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This legislation requires all digital asset managers, providers and exchanges to be registered with the Korea Financial Intelligence Unit in order to operate in South Korea.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Registering with this unit requires that all exchanges are certified by the Information Security Management System and that they ensure all customers have real name bank accounts.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] It also requires that the CEO and board members of the exchanges have not been convicted of any crimes and that the exchange holds sufficient levels of deposit insurance to cover losses arising from hacks.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Switzerland was one of the first countries to implement the FATF's Travel Rule.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] FINMA, the Swiss regulator, issued its own guidance to VASPs in 2019.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The guidance followed the FATF's Recommendation 16, with stricter requirements.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] According to FINMA's requirements, VASPs need to verify the identity of the beneficiary of the transfer.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In April 2021, the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey banned the use of cryptocurrencies and cryptoassets for making purchases on the grounds that the use of cryptocurrencies for such payments poses significant transaction risks.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In the United Kingdom, as of 10 January 2021, all cryptocurrency firms, such as exchanges, advisors and professionals that have either a presence, market product or provide services within the UK market must register with the Financial Conduct Authority.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 27 June 2021, the financial watchdog demanded that Binance cease all regulated activities in the UK.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In November 2024, the incoming Labour government confirmed that it will proceed with the regulation of cryptoassets and new UK requirements are expected to come into force in 2026.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In 2021, 17 US states passed laws and resolutions concerning cryptocurrency regulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This led the Securities and Exchange Commission to start considering what steps to take.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 8 July 2021, Senator Elizabeth Warren, part of the Senate Banking Committee, wrote to the chairman of the SEC and demanded answers on cryptocurrency regulation due to the increase in cryptocurrency exchange use and the danger this posed to consumers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 5 August 2021, the chairman, Gary Gensler, responded to Warren's letter and called for legislation focused on "crypto trading, lending and DeFi platforms," because of how vulnerable investors could be when they traded on crypto trading platforms without a broker.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] He also argued that many tokens in the crypto market may be unregistered securities without required disclosures or market oversight.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Additionally, Gensler did not hold back in his criticism of stablecoins.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] These tokens, which are pegged to the value of fiat currencies, may allow individuals to bypass important public policy goals related to traditional banking and financial systems, such as anti-money laundering, tax compliance, and sanctions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 19 October 2021, the first bitcoin-linked exchange-traded fund (ETF) from ProShares started trading on the NYSE under the ticker "BITO." ProShares CEO Michael L.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Sapir said the ETF would expose bitcoin to a wider range of investors without the hassle of setting up accounts with cryptocurrency providers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Ian Balina, the CEO of Token Metrics, stated that SEC approval of the ETF was a significant endorsement for the crypto industry because many regulators globally were not in favor of crypto, and retail investors were hesitant to accept crypto.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This event would eventually open more opportunities for new capital and new people in this space.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The Department of the Treasury, on 20 May 2021, announced that it would require any transfer worth $10,000 or more to be reported to the Internal Revenue Service since cryptocurrency already posed a problem where illegal activity like tax evasion was facilitated broadly.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] This release from the IRS was a part of efforts to promote better compliance and consider more severe penalties for tax evaders.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 17 February 2022, the Department of Justice named Eun Young Choi as the first director of a National Cryptocurrency Enforcement Team to help identify and deal with misuse of cryptocurrencies and other digital assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The Biden administration faced a dilemma as it tried to develop regulations for the cryptocurrency industry.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On one hand, officials were hesitant to restrict a growing industry.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On the other hand, they were committed to preventing illegal cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] To reconcile these conflicting goals, on 9 March 2022, Biden issued an executive order.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Followed this, on 16 September 2022, the Comprehensive Framework for Responsible Development of Digital Assets document was released to support development of cryptocurrencies and restrict their illegal use.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The executive order included all digital assets, but cryptocurrencies posed both the greatest security risks and potential economic benefits.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] Though this might not address all of the challenges in crypto industry, it was a significant milestone in the US cryptocurrency regulation history.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In February 2023, the SEC ruled that cryptocurrency exchange Kraken's estimated $42 billion in staked assets globally operated as an illegal securities seller.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The company agreed to a $30 million settlement with the SEC and to cease selling its staking service in the US.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The case would impact other major crypto exchanges operating staking programs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] On 23 March 2023, the SEC issued an alert to investors stating that firms offering crypto asset securities might not be complying with US laws.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] The SEC argued that unregistered offerings of crypto asset securities might not include important information.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p01] In addition the order prohibits the establishment, issuance or promotion of Central bank digital currency and establishes a group tasked with proposing a federal regulatory framework for digital assets within 180 days.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The legal status of cryptocurrencies varies substantially from country to country and is still undefined or changing in many of them.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] At least one study has shown that broad generalizations about the use of bitcoin in illicit finance are significantly overstated and that blockchain analysis is an effective crime fighting and intelligence gathering tool.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] While some countries have explicitly allowed their use and trade, others have banned or restricted it.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the Library of Congress in 2021, an "absolute ban" on trading or using cryptocurrencies applies in 9 countries: Algeria, Bangladesh, Bolivia, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In the United States and Canada, state and provincial securities regulators, coordinated through the North American Securities Administrators Association, are investigating "Bitcoin scams" and ICOs in 40 jurisdictions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Various government agencies, departments, and courts have classified bitcoin differently.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] China Central Bank banned the handling of bitcoins by financial institutions in China in early 2014.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In Russia, though owning cryptocurrency is legal, its residents are only allowed to purchase goods from other residents using the Russian ruble while nonresidents are allowed to use foreign currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulations and bans that apply to bitcoin probably extend to similar cryptocurrency systems.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In August 2018, the Bank of Thailand announced its plans to create its own cryptocurrency, the Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In March 2014, the United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruled that bitcoin will be treated as property for tax purposes.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, virtual currencies are considered commodities subject to capital gains tax.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] As the popularity and demand for cryptocurrencies has increased, so have concerns that they offer an unregulated person-to-person global economy that may become a threat to society.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Concerns abound that they may become tools for anonymous web criminals.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency networks display a lack of regulation that has been criticized as enabling criminals who seek to evade taxes and launder money.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Money laundering issues are also present in regular bank transfers, however with bank-to-bank wire transfers for instance, the account holder must provide a proven identity.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Transactions that occur through the use and exchange of these cryptocurrencies are independent from formal banking systems, and therefore can make tax evasion simpler for individuals.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Since charting taxable income is based upon what a recipient reports to the revenue service, it becomes extremely difficult to account for transactions made using cryptocurrencies, a mode of exchange that is complex and difficult to track.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Systems of anonymity that most cryptocurrencies offer can also serve as a means to launder money.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Rather than laundering money through an intricate network of financial actors and offshore bank accounts, laundering money through cryptocurrencies can be achieved through anonymous transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency makes legal enforcement against extremist groups more complicated, which consequently strengthens them.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] White supremacist Richard Spencer declared bitcoin the "currency of the alt-right".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In February 2014, the world's largest bitcoin exchange, Mt.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Likely due to theft, the company claimed that it had lost nearly 750,000 bitcoins belonging to their clients.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This added up to approximately 7% of all bitcoins in existence, worth a total of $473 million.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Gox blamed hackers, who had exploited the transaction malleability problems in the network.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The price of a bitcoin fell from a high of about $1,160 in December to under $400 in February.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 21 November 2017, Tether announced that it had been hacked, losing $31 million in USDT from its core treasury wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 7 December 2017, Slovenian cryptocurrency exchange Nicehash reported that hackers had stolen over $70 million using a hijacked company computer.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 19 December 2017, Yapian, the owner of South Korean exchange Youbit, filed for bankruptcy after suffering two hacks that year.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Customers were still granted access to 75% of their assets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In May 2018, Bitcoin Gold had its transactions hijacked and abused by unknown hackers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges lost an estimated $18m and bitcoin Gold was delisted from Bittrex after it refused to pay its share of the damages.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 13 September 2018, Homero Josh Garza was sentenced to 21 months of imprisonment, followed by three years of supervised release.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Garza had founded the cryptocurrency startups GAW Miners and ZenMiner in 2014, acknowledged in a plea agreement that the companies were part of a pyramid scheme, and pleaded guilty to wire fraud in 2015.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The SEC separately brought a civil enforcement action in the US against Garza, who was eventually ordered to pay a judgment of $9.1 million plus $700,000 in interest.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In January 2018, Japanese exchange Coincheck reported that hackers had stolen cryptocurrency worth $530 million.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2018, South Korean exchange Coinrail was hacked, losing over $37 million in crypto.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The hack worsened a cryptocurrency selloff by an additional $42 billion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 9 July 2018, the exchange Bancor, whose code and fundraising had been subjects of controversy, had $23.5 million in crypto stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2020 EU report found that users had lost crypto-assets worth hundreds of millions of US dollars in security breaches at exchanges and storage providers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Between 2011 and 2019, reported breaches ranged from four to twelve a year.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2019, more than a billion dollars' worth of cryptoassets was reported stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Stolen assets "typically find their way to illegal markets and are used to fund further criminal activity".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] According to the UK 2020 national risk assessment—a comprehensive assessment of money laundering and terrorist financing risk in the UK—the risk of using cryptoassets such as bitcoin for money laundering and terrorism financing is assessed as "medium" (from "low" in the previous 2017 report).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars suggested that the money laundering opportunities may be more perceived than real.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Blockchain analysis company Chainalysis concluded that illicit activities like cybercrime, money laundering and terrorism financing made up only 0.15% of all crypto transactions conducted in 2021, representing a total of $14 billion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In December 2021, Monkey Kingdom, a NFT project based in Hong Kong, lost US$1.3 million worth of cryptocurrencies via a phishing link used by the hacker.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 2 November 2023, Sam Bankman-Fried was pronounced guilty on seven counts of fraud related to FTX.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Federal criminal court sentencing experts speculated on the potential amount of prison time likely to be meted out.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 28 March 2024, the court sentenced Bankman-Fried to 25 years in prison.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] According to blockchain data company Chainalysis, criminals laundered $8.6 billion worth of cryptocurrency in 2021, up 30% from the previous year.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The data suggests that rather than managing numerous illicit havens, cybercriminals make use of a small group of purpose-built centralized exchanges for sending and receiving illicit cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2021, those exchanges received 47% of funds sent by crime-linked addresses.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost $2.2 billion worth of cryptocurrencies was embezzled from decentralized finance protocols in 2021, which represents 72% of all cryptocurrency theft in 2021.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Notable businesses include Garantex, Eggchange, Cashbank, Buy-Bitcoin, Tetchange, Bitzlato, and Suex, which was sanctioned by the U.S. in 2021.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitzlato founder and owner Anatoly Legkodymov was arrested following money-laundering charges by the United States Department of Justice.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Dark money has also been flowing into Russia through a dark web marketplace called Hydra, which is powered by cryptocurrency, and enjoyed more than $1 billion in sales in 2020, according to Chainalysis.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The platform demands that sellers liquidate cryptocurrency only through certain regional exchanges, which has made it difficult for investigators to trace the money.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Almost 74% of ransomware revenue in 2021 — over $400 million worth of cryptocurrency — went to software strains likely affiliated with Russia, where oversight is notoriously limited.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, RenBridge—an unregulated alternative to exchanges for transferring value between blockchains—was found to be responsible for the laundering of at least $540 million since 2020.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] It is especially popular with people attempting to launder money from theft.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This includes a cyberattack on Japanese crypto exchange Liquid that has been linked to North Korea.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Properties of cryptocurrencies gave them popularity in applications such as a safe haven in banking crises and means of payment, which also led to the cryptocurrency use in controversial settings in the form of online black markets, such as Silk Road.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The original Silk Road was shut down in October 2013 and there have been two more versions in use since then.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In the year following the initial shutdown of Silk Road, the number of prominent dark markets increased from four to twelve, while the amount of drug listings increased from 18,000 to 32,000.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Darknet markets present challenges in regard to their legality.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency used in dark markets are not clearly or legally classified in almost all parts of the world.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In the US, bitcoins are regarded as "virtual assets".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This type of ambiguous classification puts pressure on law enforcement agencies around the world to adapt to the shifting drug trade of dark markets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Various studies have found that crypto-trading is rife with wash trading, a process, illegal in some jurisdictions, involving buyers and sellers being the same person or group, and which may be used to manipulate the price of a cryptocurrency or inflate volume artificially.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Exchanges with higher volumes can demand higher premiums from token issuers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] A study from 2019 concluded that up to 80% of trades on unregulated cryptocurrency exchanges could be wash trades.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] A 2019 report by Bitwise Asset Management claimed that 95% of all bitcoin trading volume reported on major website CoinMarketCap had been artificially generated, and of 81 exchanges studied, only 10 provided legitimate volume figures.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, cryptocurrencies attracted attention when Western nations imposed severe economic sanctions on Russia in the aftermath of its invasion of Ukraine in February.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] However, American sources warned in March that some crypto-transactions could potentially be used to evade economic sanctions against Russia and Belarus.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In April 2022, the computer programmer Virgil Griffith received a five-year prison sentence in the US for attending a Pyongyang cryptocurrency conference, where he gave a presentation on blockchains which might be used for sanctions evasion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The Bank for International Settlements summarized several criticisms of cryptocurrencies in Chapter V of their 2018 annual report.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The criticisms include the lack of stability in their price, the high energy consumption, high and variable transactions costs, the poor security and fraud at cryptocurrency exchanges, vulnerability to debasement (from forking), and the influence of miners.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrencies have been compared to Ponzi schemes, pyramid schemes and economic bubbles, such as housing market bubbles.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Regulators in several countries have warned against cryptocurrency and some have taken measures to dissuade users.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] However, research in 2021 by the UK's financial regulator suggests such warnings either went unheard, or were ignored.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Fewer than one in 10 potential cryptocurrency buyers were aware of consumer warnings on the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) website, and 12% of crypto users were not aware that their holdings were not protected by statutory compensation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Of 1,000 respondents between the ages of eighteen and forty, 70% wrongly assumed cryptocurrencies were regulated, 75% of younger crypto investors claimed to be driven by competition with friends and family, and 58% said that social media enticed them to make high risk investments.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The FCA recommends making use of its warning list, which flags unauthorized financial firms.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Many banks do not offer virtual currency services themselves and can refuse to do business with virtual currency companies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2014, Gareth Murphy, a senior banking officer, suggested that the widespread adoption of cryptocurrencies may lead to too much money being obfuscated, blinding economists who would use such information to better steer the economy.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] While traditional financial products have strong consumer protections in place, there is no intermediary with the power to limit consumer losses if bitcoins are lost or stolen.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] One of the features cryptocurrency lacks in comparison to credit cards, for example, is consumer protection against fraud, such as chargebacks.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The French regulator Autorité des marchés financiers (AMF) lists 16 websites of companies that solicit investment in cryptocurrency without being authorized to do so in France.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] An October 2021 paper by the National Bureau of Economic Research found that bitcoin suffers from systemic risk as the top 10,000 addresses control about one-third of all bitcoin in circulation.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] It is even worse for miners, with 0.01% controlling 50% of the capacity.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] According to researcher Flipside Crypto, less than 2% of anonymous accounts control 95% of all available bitcoin supply.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This is considered risky as a great deal of the market is in the hands of a few entities.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] A paper by John Griffin, a finance professor at the University of Texas, and Amin Shams, a graduate student, found that in 2017 the price of bitcoin had been substantially inflated using another cryptocurrency, Tether.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Roger Lowenstein, author of "*Bank of America: The Epic Struggle to Create the Federal Reserve,*" said in a 2022 New York Times story that FTX currency exchange will face over $8 billion in claims.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Non-fungible tokens (NFTs) are digital assets that represent art, collectibles, gaming, etc.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Like crypto, their data is stored on the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] NFTs are bought and traded using cryptocurrency.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The Ethereum blockchain was the first place where NFTs were implemented, but now many other blockchains have created their own versions of NFTs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] According to Vanessa Grellet, renowned panelist in blockchain conferences, there was an increasing interest from traditional stock exchanges in crypto-assets at the end of the 2010s, while crypto-exchanges such as Coinbase were gradually entering the traditional financial markets.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This convergence marked a significant trend where conventional financial actors were adopting blockchain technology to enhance operational efficiency, while the crypto world introduced innovations like Security Token Offering (STO), enabling new ways of fundraising.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Tokenization, turning assets such as real estate, investment funds, and private equity into blockchain-based tokens, had the potential to make traditionally illiquid assets more accessible to investors.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Despite the regulatory risks associated with such developments, major financial institutions, including JPMorgan Chase, were actively working on blockchain initiatives, exemplified by the creation of Quorum, a private blockchain platform.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] As the first big Wall Street bank to embrace cryptocurrencies, Morgan Stanley announced on 17 March 2021 that they will be offering access to bitcoin funds for their wealthy clients through three funds which enable bitcoin ownership for investors with an aggressive risk tolerance.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] BNY Mellon on 11 February 2021 announced that it would begin offering cryptocurrency services to its clients.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] On 20 April 2021, Venmo added support to its platform to enable customers to buy, hold and sell cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In October 2021, financial services company Mastercard announced it is working with digital asset manager Bakkt on a platform that would allow any bank or merchant on the Mastercard network to offer cryptocurrency services.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining for proof-of-work (PoW) cryptocurrencies requires enormous amounts of electricity and consequently comes with a large carbon footprint due to causing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Proof-of-work blockchains such as bitcoin, Ethereum, Litecoin, and Monero were estimated to have added between 3 million and 15 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) to the atmosphere in the period from 1 January 2016 to 30 June 2017.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] By November 2018, bitcoin was estimated to have an annual energy consumption of 45.8TWh, generating 22.0 to 22.9 million tons of CO2, rivalling nations like Jordan and Sri Lanka.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] By the end of 2021, bitcoin was estimated to produce 65.4 million tons of CO2, as much as Greece, and consume between 91 and 177 terawatt-hours annually.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Critics have also identified a large electronic waste problem in disposing of mining rigs.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Mining hardware is improving at a fast rate, quickly resulting in older generations of hardware.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin is the least energy-efficient cryptocurrency, using 707.6 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Before June 2021, China was the primary location for bitcoin mining.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] However, due to concerns over power usage and other factors, China forced out bitcoin operations, at least temporarily.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] As a result, the United States promptly emerged as the top global leader in the industry.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] An example of a gross amount of electronic waste associated with bitcoin mining operations in the US is a facility located in Dalton, Georgia which is consuming nearly the same amount of electricity as the combined power usage of 97,000 households in its vicinity.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Another example is that Riot Platforms operates a bitcoin mining facility in Rockdale, Texas, which consumes approximately as much electricity as the nearby 300,000 households.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This makes it the most energy-intensive bitcoin mining operation in the United States.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The world's second-largest cryptocurrency, Ethereum, uses 62.56 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] XRP is the world's most energy efficient cryptocurrency, using 0.0079 kilowatt-hours of electricity per transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Although the biggest PoW blockchains consume energy on the scale of medium-sized countries, the annual power demand from proof-of-stake (PoS) blockchains is on a scale equivalent to a housing estate.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] *The Times* identified six "environmentally friendly" cryptocurrencies: Bitgreen, Cardano, Chia, IOTA, Nano, and Solarcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Academics and researchers have used various methods for estimating the energy use and energy efficiency of blockchains.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This equates to Polkadot consuming 7 times the electricity of an average U.S. home, Cardano 57 homes and Solana 200 times as much.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The research concluded that PoS networks consumed 0.001% the electricity of the bitcoin network.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] University College London researchers reached a similar conclusion.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Variable renewable energy power stations could invest in bitcoin mining to reduce curtailment, hedge electricity price risk, stabilize the grid, increase the profitability of renewable energy power stations and therefore accelerate transition to sustainable energy.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] There are also purely technical elements in play.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] For example, technological advancement in cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin result in high up-front costs to miners in the form of specialized hardware and software.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Cryptocurrency transactions are normally irreversible after a number of blocks confirm the transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Additionally, cryptocurrency private keys can be permanently lost from local storage due to malware, data loss, or simply carelessness.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] This precludes the cryptocurrency from any usage whatsoever, permanently, thus removing it from the market.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In September 2015, the establishment of the peer-reviewed academic journal *Ledger* (ISSN 2379-5980) was announced.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] It covers studies of cryptocurrencies and related technologies, and is published by the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which will then be timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address in the first page of their papers.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] A number of aid agencies have started accepting donations in cryptocurrencies, including UNICEF.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Christopher Fabian, principal adviser at UNICEF Innovation, said the children's fund would uphold donor protocols, meaning that people making donations online would have to pass checks before they were allowed to deposit funds.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in 2021, there was a backlash against donations in bitcoin because of the environmental emissions it caused.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Some agencies stopped accepting bitcoin and others turned to "greener" cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The U.S. arm of Greenpeace stopped accepting bitcoin donations after seven years.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2022, the Ukrainian government raised over US$10,000,000 worth of aid through cryptocurrency following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Bitcoin was characterized as a speculative bubble in 2014–2018 by eight winners of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences: Angus Deaton, Oliver Hart, James Heckman, Paul Krugman, Thomas Sargent, Robert J.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Shiller, Joseph Stiglitz, and Richard Thaler; and in 2013–2018 by central bank officials including Agustín Carstens (Mexico), Vítor Constâncio (Portugal), Alan Greenspan (US), and Nout Wellink (Netherlands).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Investors Warren Buffett and George Soros have respectively characterized it in 2014–2018 as a "mirage" and a "bubble".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Business executives Jack Ma and JP Morgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon have called it in 2017–2018 a "bubble" and a "fraud", respectively, although Jamie Dimon later said in 2018 that he regretted stating bitcoin was a fraud.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Fink in 2017 called bitcoin an "index of money laundering".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In June 2022, business magnate Bill Gates said that cryptocurrencies are "100% based on greater fool theory".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Legal scholars criticize the lack of regulation, which hinders conflict resolution when crypto assets are at the center of a legal dispute, for example a divorce or an inheritance.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In Switzerland, jurists generally deny that cryptocurrencies are objects that fall under property law, as cryptocurrencies do not belong to any class of legally defined objects (*Typenzwang*, the legal numerus clausus).
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Therefore, it is debated whether anybody could even be sued for embezzlement of cryptocurrency if they had access to someone's wallet.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] However, in the law of obligations and contract law, any kind of object would be legally valid, but the object would have to be tied to an identified counterparty.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] However, inasmuch the more popular cryptocurrencies can be freely and quickly exchanged into legal tender, they are financial assets and have to be taxed and accounted for as such.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] Losses associated with cryptocurrency investments have been linked to suicides.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] In 2018, an increase in crypto-related suicides was noticed after the cryptocurrency market crashed in August.
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The situation was particularly critical in Korea as crypto traders were on "suicide watch".
[src:cryptocurrency/cryptocurrency-p02] The May 2022 collapse of the Luna currency operated by Terra also led to reports of suicidal investors in crypto-related subreddits.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] The currency was launched in January 2014 as "Xcoin" by Evan Duffield, as a fork of the Bitcoin protocol.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] It is an altcoin and in its early days it was subject to pump and dump speculation.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] It was rebranded as Darkcoin, which received press for being used in dark net markets.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] In March 2015, it rebranded again with the name Dash as a portmanteau of 'digital cash'.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] As of August 2016, Dash is no longer used in any major dark net markets.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] In early 2017, Duffield, who lived in the Phoenix area, USA, and some other people working on Dash took space in a business incubator at Arizona State University, USA.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] The Dash DAO later funded a blockchain research lab at ASU.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] As of April 2018, Dash's market capitalization was around $4.3 billion and it was one of the top 12 cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] As of February 2019, Dash was the most popular cryptocurrency in Venezuela according to *Der Spiegel*.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] In Venezuela, it was often used alongside Bitcoin and Petro, with Petro basing much of its technology from Dash.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] On 1 October 2018, Petro switched to an X11 algorithm-based design, which was copied from Dash.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] Dash was designed to allow transactions to occur quickly and to implement a governance structure that addresses perceived shortcomings in Bitcoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] Governance is managed through a form of decentralized autonomous organization in which decisions are made via a blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] The system includes standard nodes and miners.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] The system's decentralization has been criticized due to a mishap during its initial coin distribution, which allowed too many coins to be distributed at release.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] This concentrated wealth within a small group of early adopters, giving them disproportionate power in decisions regarding the currency’s future.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] As of 2018, coins were mined using a proof of work algorithm with a hash function called "X11," which involves eleven rounds of hashing.
[src:cryptocurrency/dash-cryptocurrency] The average time to mine a block was around two and a half minutes.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital currencies exhibit properties similar to traditional currencies, but generally do not have a classical physical form of fiat currency historically that can be held in the hand, like currencies with printed banknotes or minted coins.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] However, they do have a physical form in an unclassical sense coming from the computer to computer and computer to human interactions and the information and processing power of the servers that store and keep track of money.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] This unclassical physical form allows nearly instantaneous transactions over the internet and vastly lowers the cost associated with distributing notes and coins: for example, of the types of money in the UK economy, 3% are notes and coins, and 79% as electronic money (in the form of bank deposits).
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Usually not issued by a governmental body, virtual currencies are not considered a legal tender and they enable ownership transfer across governmental borders.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] This type of currency may be used to buy physical goods and services, but may also be restricted to certain communities such as for use inside an online game.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital money can either be centralized, where there is a central point of control over the money supply (for instance, a bank), or decentralized, where the control over the money supply is predetermined or agreed upon democratically.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Precursory ideas for digital currencies were presented in electronic payment methods such as the Sabre (travel reservation system).
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 1983, a research paper titled "Blind Signatures for Untraceable Payments" by David Chaum introduced the idea of digital cash.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 1989, he founded DigiCash, an electronic cash company, in Amsterdam to commercialize the ideas in his research.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] e-gold was the first widely used Internet money, introduced in 1996, and grew to several million users before the US Government shut it down in 2008. e-gold has been referenced to as "digital currency" by both US officials and academia.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 1997, Coca-Cola offered buying from vending machines using mobile payments.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] PayPal launched its USD-denominated service in 1998.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 2009, bitcoin was launched, which marked the start of decentralized blockchain-based digital currencies with no central server, and no tangible assets held in reserve.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Also known as cryptocurrencies, blockchain-based digital currencies proved resistant to attempt by government to regulate them, because there was no central organization or person with the power to turn them off.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Origins of digital currencies date back to the 1990s Dot-com bubble.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Another known digital currency service was Liberty Reserve, founded in 2006; it lets users convert dollars or euros to Liberty Reserve Dollars or Euros, and exchange them freely with one another at a 1% fee.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Several digital currency operations were reputed to be used for Ponzi schemes and money laundering, and were prosecuted by the U.S. government for operating without MSB licenses.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Q coins or QQ coins, were used as a type of commodity-based digital currency on Tencent QQ's messaging platform and emerged in early 2005.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Q coins were so effective in China that they were said to have had a destabilizing effect on the Chinese yuan currency due to speculation.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Recent interest in cryptocurrencies has prompted renewed interest in digital currencies, with bitcoin, introduced in 2008, becoming the most widely used and accepted digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital currency is a term that refers to a specific type of electronic currency with specific properties.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital currency is also a term used to include the meta-group of sub-types of digital currency, the specific meaning can only be determined within the specific legal or contextual case.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Legally and technically, there already are a myriad of legal definitions of digital currency and the many digital currency sub-types.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Combining different possible properties, there exists an extensive number of implementations creating many and numerous sub-types of digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Many governmental jurisdictions have implemented their own unique definition for digital currency, virtual currency, cryptocurrency, e-money, network money, e-cash, and other types of digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Within any specific government jurisdiction, different agencies and regulators define different and often conflicting meanings for the different types of digital currency based on the specific properties of a specific currency type or sub-type.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A virtual currency has been defined in 2012 by the European Central Bank as "a type of unregulated, digital money, which is issued and usually controlled by its developers, and used and accepted among the members of a specific virtual community".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The US Department of Treasury in 2013 defined it more tersely as "a medium of exchange that operates like a currency in some environments, but does not have all the attributes of real currency".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] According to the European Central Bank's 2015 "Virtual currency schemes – a further analysis" report, virtual currency is a digital representation of value, not issued by a central bank, credit institution or e-money institution, which, in some circumstances, can be used as an alternative to money.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In the previous report of October 2012, the virtual currency was defined as a type of unregulated, digital money, which is issued and usually controlled by its developers, and used and accepted among the members of a specific virtual community.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] According to the Bank for International Settlements' November 2015 "Digital currencies" report, it is an asset represented in digital form and having some monetary characteristics.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital currency can be denominated to a sovereign currency and issued by the issuer responsible to redeem digital money for cash.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In that case, digital currency represents electronic money (e-money).
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital currency denominated in its own units of value or with decentralized or automatic issuance will be considered as a virtual currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] As such, bitcoin is a digital currency but also a type of virtual currency. bitcoin and its alternatives are based on cryptographic algorithms, so these kinds of virtual currencies are also called cryptocurrencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Cryptocurrency is a sub-type of digital currency and a digital asset that relies on cryptography to chain together digital signatures of asset transfers, peer-to-peer networking and decentralization.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In some cases a proof-of-work or proof-of-stake scheme is used to create and manage the currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Cryptocurrencies can allow electronic money systems to be decentralized.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] When implemented with a blockchain, the digital ledger system or record keeping system uses cryptography to edit separate shards of database entries that are distributed across many separate servers.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The first and most popular system is bitcoin, a peer-to-peer electronic monetary system based on cryptography.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Most of the traditional money supply is bank money held on computers.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] They are considered digital currency in some cases.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] One could argue that our increasingly cashless society means that all currencies are becoming digital currencies, but they are not presented to us as such.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Currency can be exchanged electronically using debit cards and credit cards using electronic funds transfer at point of sale.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A number of electronic money systems use contactless payment transfer in order to facilitate easy payment and give the payee more confidence in not letting go of their electronic wallet during the transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A central bank digital currency (CBDC) is a form of universally accessible digital money in a nation and holds the same value as the country's paper currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Like a cryptocurrency, a CBDC is held in the form of tokens.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] CBDCs are different from regular digital cash forms like in online bank accounts because CBDCs are established through the central bank within a country, with liabilities held by one's government, rather than from a commercial bank.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Approximately nine countries have already established a CBDC, with interest in the system increasing highly throughout the world.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In these nations, CBDCs have been used as a form of exchange and a way for governments to try to prevent risks from occurring within their financial systems.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A major problem with central bank digital currencies is deciding whether the currency should be easily trackable.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] If it's traceable, the government has more control than it currently does.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Additionally, there's a technical aspect to consider: whether CBDCs should be based on tokens or accounts and how much anonymity users should have.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Digital Currency has been implemented in some cases as a decentralized system of any combination of currency issuance, ownership record, ownership transfer authorization and validation, and currency storage.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Per the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), "These schemes do not distinguish between users based on location, and therefore allow value to be transferred between users across borders.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Since 2001, the European Union has implemented the E-Money Directive "on the taking up, pursuit and prudential supervision of the business of electronic money institutions" last amended in 2009.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In the United States, electronic money is governed by Article 4A of the Uniform Commercial Code for wholesale transactions and the Electronic Fund Transfer Act for consumer transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Provider's responsibility and consumer's liability are regulated under Regulation E.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Virtual currencies pose challenges for central banks, financial regulators, departments or ministries of finance, as well as fiscal authorities and statistical authorities.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] As of 2016, over 24 countries are investing in distributed ledger technologies (DLT) with $1.4bn in investments.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In addition, over 90 central banks are engaged in DLT discussions, including implications of a central bank issued digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In March 2018, the Marshall Islands became the first country to issue their own cryptocurrency and certify it as legal tender; the currency is called the "sovereign".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The US Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) has determined virtual currencies are properly defined as commodities in 2015.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The CFTC warned investors against pump and dump schemes that use virtual currencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The US Internal Revenue Service (IRS) ruling Notice 2014-21 defines any virtual currency, cryptocurrency and digital currency as property; gains and losses are taxable within standard property policies.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] On 20 March 2013, the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network issued a guidance to clarify how the U.S.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Bank Secrecy Act applied to persons creating, exchanging, and transmitting virtual currencies.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In May 2014 the US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) "warned about the hazards of bitcoin and other virtual currencies".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In July 2014, the New York State Department of Financial Services proposed the most comprehensive regulation of virtual currencies to date, commonly called BitLicense.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] It has gathered input from bitcoin supporters and the financial industry through public hearings and a comment period until 21 October 2014 to customize the rules.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The proposal per NY DFS press release "sought to strike an appropriate balance that helps protect consumers and root out illegal activity".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] It has been criticized by smaller companies to favor established institutions, and Chinese bitcoin exchanges have complained that the rules are "overly broad in its application outside the United States".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Bank of Canada has explored the possibility of creating a version of its currency on the blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Bank of Canada teamed up with the nation's five largest banks – and the blockchain consulting firm R3 – for what was known as Project Jasper.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In a simulation run in 2016, the central bank issued CAD-Coins onto a blockchain similar Ethereum.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The banks used the CAD-Coins to exchange money the way they do at the end of each day to settle their master accounts.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 2016, Fan Yifei, a deputy governor of China's central bank, the People's Bank of China (PBOC), wrote that "the conditions are ripe for digital currencies, which can reduce operating costs, increase efficiency and enable a wide range of new applications".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] According to Fan Yifei, the best way to take advantage of the situation is for central banks to take the lead, both in supervising private digital currencies and in developing digital legal tender of their own.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In October 2019, the PBOC announced that a digital renminbi would be released after years of preparation.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The version of the currency, known as DCEP (Digital Currency Electronic Payment), is based on cryptocurrency which can be "decoupled" from the banking system.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The announcement received a variety of responses: some believe it is more about domestic control and surveillance.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In December 2020, the PBOC distributed CN¥20 million worth of digital renminbi to the residents of Suzhou through a lottery program to further promote the government-backed digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Recipients of the currency could make both offline and online purchases, expanding on an earlier trial that did not require internet connection through the inclusion of online stores in the program.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Around 20,000 transactions were reported by the e-commerce company JD.com in the first 24 hours of the trial.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Contrary to other online payment platforms such as Alipay or WeChat Pay, the digital currency does not have transaction fees.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Danish government proposed getting rid of the obligation for selected retailers to accept payment in cash, moving the country closer to a "cashless" economy.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Danish Chamber of Commerce is backing the move.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Nearly a third of the Danish population uses MobilePay, a smartphone application for transferring money.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A law passed by the National Assembly of Ecuador gives the government permission to make payments in electronic currency and proposes the creation of a national digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] "Electronic money will stimulate the economy; it will be possible to attract more Ecuadorian citizens, especially those who do not have checking or savings accounts and credit cards alone.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The electronic currency will be backed by the assets of the Central Bank of Ecuador", the National Assembly said in a statement.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In December 2015, Sistema de Dinero Electrónico ("electronic money system") was launched, making Ecuador the first country with a state-run electronic payment system.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] On 9 June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador has become the first country in the world to officially classify bitcoin as legal currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Starting 90 days after approval, every business must accept bitcoin as legal tender for goods or services, unless it is unable to provide the technology needed to do the transaction.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Dutch central bank is experimenting with a blockchain-based virtual currency called "DNBCoin".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Unified Payments Interface (UPI) is a real-time payment system for instant money transfers between any two bank accounts held in participating banks in India.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The interface has been developed by the National Payments Corporation of India and is regulated by the Reserve Bank of India.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] This digital payment system is available 24 hours a day, every day of the year.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] UPI is agnostic to the type of user and is used for person to person, person to business, business to person and business to business transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Transactions can be initiated by the payer or the payee.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] To identify a bank account it uses a unique Virtual Payment Address (VPA) of the type 'accountID@bankID'.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The VPA can be assigned by the bank, but can also be self specified just like an email address.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The simplest and most common form of VPA is 'mobilenumber@upi'.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Money can be transferred from one VPA to another or from one VPA to any bank account in a participating bank using account number and bank branch details.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Transfers can be inter-bank or intra-bank.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] UPI has no intermediate holding pond for money.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] It withdraws funds directly from the bank account of the sender and deposits them directly into the recipient's bank account whenever a transaction is requested.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A sender can initiate and authorise a transfer using a two step secure process: login using a pass code → initiate → verify using a passcode.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] A receiver can initiate a payment request on the system to send the payer a notification or by presenting a QR code.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] On receiving the request, the payer can decline or confirm the payment using the same two step process: login → confirm → verify.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The system is extraordinarily user friendly to the extent that even technophobes and barely literate users are adopting it in huge numbers.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Government-controlled Sberbank of Russia owns YooMoney – electronic payment service and digital currency of the same name.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Sweden completed the replacement of all physical banknotes and most coins by mid-2017.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] However, the new banknotes and coins of the Swedish krona will probably be circulating at about half the 2007 peak of 12,494 kronor per capita.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Riksbank is planning to begin discussions of an electronic currency issued by the central bank to which "is not to replace cash, but to act as complement to it".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Deputy Governor Cecilia Skingsley states that cash will continue to spiral out of use in Sweden, and while it is currently fairly easy to get cash in Sweden, it is often very difficult to deposit it into bank accounts, especially in rural areas.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] No decision has been currently made about the decision to create "e-krona".
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 2016, a city government first accepted digital currency in payment of city fees.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Zug, Switzerland, added bitcoin as a means of paying small amounts, up to SFr 200, in a test and an attempt to advance Zug as a region that is advancing future technologies.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In order to reduce risk, Zug immediately converts any bitcoin received into the Swiss currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Swiss Federal Railways, government-owned railway company of Switzerland, sells bitcoins at its ticket machines.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 2016, the UK's chief scientific adviser, Sir Mark Walport, advised the government to consider using a blockchain-based digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The chief economist of Bank of England, the central bank of the United Kingdom, proposed the abolition of paper currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Bank has also taken an interest in blockchain.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] In 2016 it has embarked on a multi-year research programme to explore the implications of a central bank issued digital currency.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Bank of England has produced several research papers on the topic.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] One suggests that the economic benefits of issuing a digital currency on a distributed ledger could add as much as 3 percent to a country's economic output.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The Bank said that it wanted the next version of the bank's basic software infrastructure to be compatible with distributed ledgers.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Government attitude dictates the tendency among established heavy financial actors that both are risk-averse and conservative.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] None of these offered services around cryptocurrencies and much of the criticism came from them.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] It will work with bitcoin and Ethereum with general availability scheduled for 2019.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Hard electronic currency does not have the ability to be disputed or reversed when used.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] It is nearly impossible to reverse a transaction, justified or not.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Contrarily, soft electronic currency payments can be reversed.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Usually, when a payment is reversed there is a "clearing time." A hard currency can be "softened" with a third-party service.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Many existing digital currencies have not yet seen widespread usage, and may not be easily used or exchanged.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Banks generally do not accept or offer services for them.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] There are concerns that cryptocurrencies are extremely risky due to their very high volatility and potential for pump and dump schemes.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Regulators in several countries have warned against their use and some have taken concrete regulatory measures to dissuade users.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The non-cryptocurrencies are all centralized.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] As such, they may be shut down or seized by a government at any time.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] The more anonymous a currency is, the more attractive it is to criminals, regardless of the intentions of its creators. bitcoin has also been criticised for its energy inefficient SHA-256-based proof of work.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] According to Barry Eichengreen, an economist known for his work on monetary and financial economics, "cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are too volatile to possess the essential attributes of money.
[src:cryptocurrency/digital-currency] Stablecoins have fragile currency pegs that diminish their utility in transactions.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] The Litecoin blockchain is similar to the bitcoin codebase, modified for lower transaction fees.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] By 2011, bitcoin mining was largely performed by GPUs.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] This raised concern in some users that mining now had a high barrier to entry, and that CPU resources were becoming obsolete and worthless for mining.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] Using code from bitcoin, a new alternative currency was created called *Tenebrix* (TBX).
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] Tenebrix replaced the SHA-256 rounds in bitcoin's mining algorithm with the *scrypt* function, which had been specifically designed in 2009 to be expensive to accelerate with FPGA or ASIC chips.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] This would allow Tenebrix to have been "GPU-resistant", and utilize the available CPU resources from bitcoin miners.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] Tenebrix itself was a successor project to an earlier cryptocurrency which replaced bitcoin's issuance schedule with a constant block reward (thus creating an unlimited money supply).
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] However, the developers included a clause in the code that would allow them to claim 7.7 million TBX for themselves at no cost, which was criticized by users.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] To address this, Charlie Lee, a Google employee who would later become engineering director at Coinbase, created an alternative version of Tenebrix called *Fairbrix* (FBX).
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] Lee released Litecoin via an open-source client on GitHub on October 7, 2011.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] After launch, the early growth of Litecoin was aided by its increasing exchange availability and liquidity on early exchanges such as BTC-e.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] During the month of November 2013, the aggregate value of Litecoin experienced massive growth which included a 100% leap within 24 hours.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] In early 2014, Lee suggested merge mining (auxPOW) Dogecoin with Litecoin to the Dogecoin community at large.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] In September 2014, Dogecoin began merge-mining with Litecoin.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] In 2020, PayPal added the ability for users to purchase a derivative of Litecoin along with bitcoin, Ethereum, and Bitcoin Cash which could not be withdrawn or spent as part of its Crypto feature.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] In September 2021, a fake press release was published on GlobeNewswire announcing a partnership between Litecoin and Walmart.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] This caused the price of Litecoin to increase by around 30%, before the press release was revealed as a hoax.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] In May 2022, MWEB (Mimblewimble Extension Blocks) upgrade was activated on the Litecoin network as a soft fork.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] This upgrade provides users with the option of sending confidential Litecoin transactions, in which the amount being sent is only known between the sender and receiver.
[src:cryptocurrency/litecoin] Third-party vendors providing point of sale infrastructure for Litecoin include BitPay.
